{"title_page": "Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song contest country\n|Name           = Azerbaijan\n|Member station = [[\u0130ctimai Television]] (\u0130TV)\n|National selection event = {{Collapsible list\n | title = '''National Final'''\n | '''Junior'''\n | 2012\n}}{{Collapsible list\n | title = '''Internal Selection'''\n | 2013, 2018\n}}\n|ESC apps       = 3\n|ESC first      = [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n|ESC last       = [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n|ESC best       = 7th: [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]]\n|ESC worst      = 16th: [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n|Website        =\n|EBU page       = http://www.junioreurovision.tv/country/azerbaijan\n|Current JESC = 2018\n}}\n'''Azerbaijan''' debuted in the '''Junior Eurovision Song Contest''' in [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junioreurovision.tv/page/blog?id=junior_2012_12_countries_to_take_part|title=Junior 2012: 12 countries to take part|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> In 2008, [[\u0130TV]] announced that Azerbaijan would take part in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2008]] in [[Limassol]], but then withdrew before the contest, because there were too few candidates for the national selection and consequently canceled its debut. \n\nAfter taking part in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013]], Azerbaijan withdrew from the contest because of unspecified reasons and on 25 July 2018, it was announced that Azerbaijan will return to the contest in {{Escyr|2018|Junior}}. Their worst result till date has been achieved by Fidan Huseynova with her song \"I Wanna Be Like You\" in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018. \u0130TV announced on 1 July 2019 that they will not take part in the {{Escyr|2019|Junior}} contest in [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/07/01/azerbaijan-withdraws-junior-eurovision-2019/|title=Azerbaijan: Withdraws From Junior Eurovision 2019|publisher=Eurovoix|date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Participation==\n<!--{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|width=15px bgcolor=gold|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|bgcolor=silver|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#c96|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FE8080|{{center|\u25c1}}\n|Last place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#A4EAA9|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete\n|}-->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Song\n!Language\n!width=50px|Place\n!width=50px|Points\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012|Junior}}\n|Suada Alakbarova and Omar Sultanov\n|\"Girls and Boys (D\u00fcnya S\u0259nindir)\"\n|[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[English language|English]]\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|49\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2013|Junior}}\n|[[Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013#Rustam Karimov|Rustam Karimov]]\n|\"Me and My Guitar\"\n|Azerbaijani, English\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|66\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate from [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]] to [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]] }}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018|Junior}}\n|Fidan Huseynova\n|\"I Wanna Be Like You\"\n|Azerbaijani, English\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|47\n|-\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2019|Junior}}}}\n|colspan=\"5\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|}\n\n===Photo gallery===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:JESC 2013 (Azerbaijan) Rustam Karimov at rehearsal 1.jpg|Rustam Karimov in Kiev ({{Escyr|2013|Junior}})\n</gallery>\n\n==Commentators and spokespersons==\n{{more citations needed section|date=November 2019}}\nThe contests are broadcast online worldwide through the official Junior Eurovision Song Contest website junioreurovision.tv and [[YouTube]]. In 2015, the online broadcasts featured commentary in English by junioreurovision.tv editor Luke Fisher and 2011 Bulgarian Junior Eurovision Song Contest entrant [[Ivan Ivanov (singer)|Ivan Ivanov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junioreurovision.tv/page/blog?id=tonight_junior_eurovision_song_contest_2015|title=Tonight: Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2015!|last=Fisher|first=Luke James|work=Junior Eurovision Song Contest \u2013 Bulgaria 2015|date=21 November 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The Azerbaijani broadcaster, \u0130TV, send their own commentary team to each contest in order to provide commentary in the [[Azerbaijani language]]. Spokespersons were also chosen by the national broadcaster in order to announce the awarding points from Azerbaijan. The table below list the details of each commentator and spokesperson since 2012.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Commentator\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007|Junior}}\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{TBA|Unknown}}\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008|Junior}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009|Junior}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010|Junior}}\u2013{{Escyr|2011|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012|Junior}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Konul Arifkizi\n|Leila Hajili\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013|Junior}}\n|Lyaman Mirzalieva\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014|Junior}}\u2013{{Escyr|2017|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018|Junior}}\n|Shafiga Efendiyeva\n|Valeh Huseynbeyli\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/11/24/azerbaijan-junior-eurovision-2018-commentator-spokesperson-revealed/|title=Azerbaijan: Junior Eurovision 2018 Commentator & Spokesperson Revealed|publisher=Eurovoix|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Bala T\u00fcrkvizyon Song Contest]] &ndash; Junior version of the Turkvision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Dance Contest]] &ndash; Dance version of the Eurovision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest]] &ndash; Senior version of the Junior Eurovision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the T\u00fcrkvizyon Song Contest]]  &ndash; A contest for countries and regions which are of [[Turkic languages|Turkic-speaking]] or [[Turkic people|Turkic ethnicity]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{URL|1=www.junioreurovision.tv/country/azerbaijan|2=Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest}} ''Official EBU Page''\n\n{{Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Junior Eurovision Song Contest}}\n[[Category:Countries in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n\n\n{{Eurovision stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=September 2012}}\n{{Infobox song contest country\n|Name           = Azerbaijan\n|Member station = [[\u0130ctimai Television]] (\u0130TV)\n|National selection event = {{Collapsible list\n | title = '''National Final'''\n | '''Junior'''\n | 2012\n}}{{Collapsible list\n | title = '''Internal Selection'''\n | 2013, 2018\n}}\n|ESC apps       = 3\n|ESC first      = [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]]\n|ESC last       = [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n|ESC best       = 7th: [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013|2013]]\n|ESC worst      = 16th: [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018|2018]]\n|Website        =\n|EBU page       = http://www.junioreurovision.tv/country/azerbaijan\n|Current JESC = 2018\n}}\n'''Azerbaijan''' debuted in the '''Junior Eurovision Song Contest''' in [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2012|2012]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junioreurovision.tv/page/blog?id=junior_2012_12_countries_to_take_part|title=Junior 2012: 12 countries to take part|publisher=[[European Broadcasting Union]]|date=1 September 2012|accessdate=3 September 2012}}</ref> In 2008, [[\u0130TV]] announced that Azerbaijan would take part in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2008]] in [[Limassol]], but then withdrew before the contest, because there were too few candidates for the national selection and consequently canceled its debut. \n\nAfter taking part in the [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013]], Azerbaijan withdrew from the contest because of unspecified reasons and on 25 July 2018, it was announced that Azerbaijan will return to the contest in {{Escyr|2018|Junior}}. Their worst result till date has been achieved by Fidan Huseynova with her song \"I Wanna Be Like You\" in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2018. \u0130TV announced on 1 July 2019 that they will not take part in the {{Escyr|2019|Junior}} contest in [[Gliwice]], [[Poland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/07/01/azerbaijan-withdraws-junior-eurovision-2019/|title=Azerbaijan: Withdraws From Junior Eurovision 2019|publisher=Eurovoix|date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Participation==\n<!--{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|+Table key\n|-\n|width=15px bgcolor=gold|{{center|1}}\n|Winner\n|-\n|bgcolor=silver|{{center|2}}\n|Second place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#c96|{{center|3}}\n|Third place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#FE8080|{{center|\u25c1}}\n|Last place\n|-\n|bgcolor=#A4EAA9|{{center|'''X'''}}\n|Entry selected but did not compete\n|}-->\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!width=30px|Year\n!Artist\n!Song\n!Language\n!width=50px|Place\n!width=50px|Points\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2012|Junior}}\n|Suada Alakbarova & Omar Sultanov\n|\"Girls and Boys (D\u00fcnya S\u0259nindir)\"\n|[[Azerbaijani language|Azerbaijani]], [[English language|English]]\n|align=center|11\n|align=center|49\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2013|Junior}}\n|[[Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013#Rustam Karimov|Rustam Karimov]]\n|\"Me and My Guitar\"\n|Azerbaijani, English\n|align=center|7\n|align=center|66\n|-\n|colspan=\"6\" data-sort-value=\"zzzzz\" {{N/A|Did not participate from [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2014|2014]] to [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2017|2017]] }}\n|-\n!{{Escyr|2018|Junior}}\n|Fidan Huseynova\n|\"I Wanna Be Like You\"\n|Azerbaijani, English\n|align=center|16\n|align=center|47\n|-\n|{{N/A|{{Escyr|2019|Junior}}}}\n|colspan=\"5\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|}\n\n===Photo gallery===\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:JESC 2013 (Azerbaijan) Rustam Karimov at rehearsal 1.jpg|Rustam Karimov at [[Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2013]], Kiev.\n</gallery>\n\n==Commentators and spokespersons==\n{{more citations needed section|date=November 2019}}\nThe contests are broadcast online worldwide through the official Junior Eurovision Song Contest website junioreurovision.tv and [[YouTube]]. In 2015, the online broadcasts featured commentary in English by junioreurovision.tv editor Luke Fisher and 2011 Bulgarian Junior Eurovision Song Contest entrant [[Ivan Ivanov (singer)|Ivan Ivanov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.junioreurovision.tv/page/blog?id=tonight_junior_eurovision_song_contest_2015|title=Tonight: Junior Eurovision Song Contest 2015!|last=Fisher|first=Luke James|work=Junior Eurovision Song Contest \u2013 Bulgaria 2015|date=21 November 2015|accessdate=21 November 2015}}</ref> The Azerbaijani broadcaster, \u0130TV, send their own commentary team to each contest in order to provide commentary in the [[Azerbaijani language]]. Spokespersons were also chosen by the national broadcaster in order to announce the awarding points from Azerbaijan. The table below list the details of each commentator and spokesperson since 2012.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"font-size:90%;\"\n|-\n!Year\n!Commentator\n!Spokesperson\n!class=\"unsortable\"|{{abbr|Ref.|Reference}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2007|Junior}}\n|rowspan=\"3\" {{TBA|Unknown}}\n|rowspan=\"4\" {{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2008|Junior}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2009|Junior}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2010|Junior}}\u2013{{Escyr|2011|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2012|Junior}}\n|rowspan=\"2\"|Konul Arifkizi\n|Leila Hajili\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2013|Junior}}\n|Lyaman Mirzalieva\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2014|Junior}}\u2013{{Escyr|2017|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2018|Junior}}\n|Shafiga Efendiyeva\n|Valeh Huseynbeyli\n|{{center|<ref>{{cite news|url=https://eurovoix.com/2018/11/24/azerbaijan-junior-eurovision-2018-commentator-spokesperson-revealed/|title=Azerbaijan: Junior Eurovision 2018 Commentator & Spokesperson Revealed|publisher=Eurovoix|access-date=24 November 2018}}</ref>}}\n|-\n!scope=\"row\"|{{Escyr|2019|Junior}}\n|{{N/A|No broadcast}}\n|{{N/A|Did not participate}}\n|\n|}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Bala T\u00fcrkvizyon Song Contest]] &ndash; Junior version of the Turkvision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Dance Contest]] &ndash; Dance version of the Eurovision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the Eurovision Song Contest]] &ndash; Senior version of the Junior Eurovision Song Contest.\n* [[Azerbaijan in the T\u00fcrkvizyon Song Contest]]  &ndash; A contest for countries and regions which are of [[Turkic languages|Turkic-speaking]] or [[Turkic people|Turkic ethnicity]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{URL|1=www.junioreurovision.tv/country/azerbaijan|2=Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest}} ''Official EBU Page''\n\n{{Azerbaijan in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest}}\n{{Junior Eurovision Song Contest}}\n[[Category:Countries in the Junior Eurovision Song Contest]]\n\n\n{{Eurovision stub}}\n", "name_user": "Dummelaksen", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParticipation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Azerbaijan_in_the_Junior_Eurovision_Song_Contest"}
{"title_page": "Slate (magazine)", "text_new": "{{short description|U.S.-based online magazine}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| logo = Slate new logo.svg\n| screenshot = Slate homepage 2013-11-09.png\n| collapsible =\n| collapsetext =\n| caption =\n| url = {{url|https://slate.com}}, {{url|https://slate.fr}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| type = Online magazine\n| registration = Optional for Slate Plus and commenting only (US readers)<br />\nMetered paywall (non-US readers)\n| language =\n| num_users =\n| content_license =\n| owner = [[The Slate Group]]\n| editor = [[Jared Hohlt]]\n| author = [[Michael Kinsley]]\n| launch_date = {{start date and age|1996}}\n| revenue =\n| alexa = {{Decrease}} 2,374 ({{as of|2020|1|3|alt=December 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/slate.com |title= Slate.com Site Info |publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |access-date= January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| political = \n| issn = 1090-6584\n| eissn = 1091-2339\n| oclc = 728292344\n| current_status = Active\n| footnotes =\n| name = ''Slate''\n| logocaption =\n}}\n'''''Slate''''' is an online magazine that covers current affairs, politics, and culture in the United States. It is known, and sometimes criticized, for adopting [[contrarian]] views, giving rise to the term \"Slate Pitches\".<ref>{{cite news |title= Contrarianism's end? |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2009/10/contrarianisms_end_1 |newspaper= [[The Economist]] |date= October 19, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite magazine |last= Weisberg |first= Jacob |title= What Makes Slate Slatey? |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/slates_10th_anniversary/2006/06/what_makes_slate_slatey.single.html |magazine= Slate |date= June 19, 2006 |quote= To be a Slatey writer, you must cut through the media welter [...] This can be done in a number of ways. [One] is to make the contrarian case that all the common assumptions about a subject are simply and hopelessly wrong.}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last= Coscarelli |first= Joe |title= Slate\u2019s Contrarian Ways Mocked On Twitter|url=http://www.mediaite.com/online/slates-contrarian-ways-mocked-on-twitter/ |publisher= [[Mediaite]] |date= October 23, 2009}}</ref> It has a generally [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] editorial stance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2014/10/21/lets-rank-the-media-from-liberal-to-conservative-based-on-their-audiences/|title=Ranking the media from liberal to conservative, based on their audiences|first=Aaron|last=Blake|date=October 21, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2005/06/wolff200506|title=No Jokes, Please, We're Liberal|first=Michael|last=Wolff|date=|website=VanityFair.com|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Winter|first1=Jessica|title=Slate Isn\u2019t Too Liberal. But\u2026|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/slate_plus/slate_fare/2014/09/is_slate_magazine_too_liberal_or_conservative_what_members_said_about_the.html|website=Slate|accessdate=21 September 2017|date=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt was created in 1996 by former ''[[The New Republic|New Republic]]'' editor [[Michael Kinsley]], initially under the ownership of [[Microsoft]] as part of [[MSN]]. In 2004, it was purchased by [[Graham Holdings|The Washington Post Company]] (later renamed the Graham Holdings Company), and since 2008 has been managed by [[The Slate Group]], an online publishing entity created by Graham Holdings. ''Slate'' is based in New York City, with an additional office in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate Magazine: Private Company Information - Businessweek |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=8200230 |publisher= Bloomberg.com |access-date= July 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'', which is updated throughout the day, covers politics, arts and culture, sports, and news. According to its former editor-in-chief [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]], the magazine is \"not fundamentally a breaking news source\", but rather aimed at helping readers to \"analyze and understand and interpret the world\" with witty and entertaining writing.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url= http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/media/2014/09/8553356/long-serving-deputy-julia-turner-takes-reins-slate |title= Long-serving deputy Julia Turner takes the reins at Slate |last= Levy |first= Nicole |date= September 30, 2014 |work= [[Politico|Capital New York]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref> As of mid-2015, it publishes about 1,500 stories per month.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |title= Unlimited FAQ |url= https://secure.slate.com/unlimited |work= Slate |access-date= July 2, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150703071551/https://secure.slate.com/unlimited |archive-date= July 3, 2015 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA French version, ''slate.fr'', was launched in February 2009 by a group of four journalists, including [[Jean-Marie Colombani]], Eric Leser, and economist [[Jacques Attali]]. Among them, the founders hold 50 percent in the publishing company, while The Slate Group holds 15 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/15/paidcontent/main4803947.shtml |work= [[CBS News]] |title= Interview: Jacob Weisberg, Chairman, Slate Group: Breaking Out of the Beltway |date= February 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2009-02-11/slate-fr-jean-marie-colombani-a-l-assaut-du-web/1387/0/315818 |title= Slate.fr: Jean-Marie Colombani \u00e0 l'assaut du Web, actualit\u00e9 Tech & Net \u2013 Le Point |magazine= [[Le Point]] |date= February 10, 2009 |access-date= April 28, 2013| language= French}}</ref> In 2011, ''slate.fr'' started a separate site covering African news, ''Slate Afrique'', with a Paris-based editorial staff.<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate Afrique |url= http://www.voxeurop.eu/en/content/source-profile/2135951-slate-afrique |access-date= July 2, 2015 |publisher= VoxEurop |date= June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is ad-supported and has been available to read free of charge since 1999, but restricted access for non-US readers via a [[metered paywall]] in 2015.\n\n==Background==\n''Slate'' features regular and semi-regular columns such as ''Explainer, Moneybox, Spectator, Transport'', and ''[[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]]''. Many of the articles are short (less than 2,000 words) and argument-driven. Around 2010, the magazine also began running long-form journalism. Many of the longer stories are an outgrowth of the \"Fresca Fellowships\", so-called because former editor Plotz liked the soft drink [[Fresca]]. \"The idea is that every writer and editor on staff has to spend a month or six weeks a year not doing their regular job, but instead working on a long, ambitious project of some sort,\" Plotz said in an interview.<ref>{{cite web |last=Levy |first=Dan |date= April 4, 2011 |title=Slate of Mind: Q&A with David Plotz |url= http://sparksheet.com/slate-of-mind-qa-with-david-plotz/ |work=Sparksheet |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'' introduced a [[paywall]]-based business model in 1998 that attracted up 20,000 subscribers but was later abandoned.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news |last= Sawers |first= Paul |date= June 8, 2015 |title= Slate slides behind a metered paywall as global readers are asked to pay $5/month|url= https://venturebeat.com/2015/06/08/slate-slides-behind-a-paywall-as-global-readers-are-asked-to-pay-5month-to-read-more-than-5-articles/ |work=[[VentureBeat]] |accessdate= July 2, 2015}}</ref> A similar subscription model was implemented in April 2001 by ''Slate''{{'}}s independently owned competitor, [[Salon.com]].\n\n''Slate'' started a daily feature, \"Today's Pictures\", on November 30, 2005, which featured 15\u201320 photographs from the archive at [[Magnum Photos]] that share a common theme. The column also features two [[Flash animation|Flash animated]] \"Interactive Essays\" a month.\n\n[[File:Slate screenshot.png|thumb|right|The design of ''Slate''{{'}}s homepage from 2006 to 2013]]\n\nOn its 10th anniversary, ''Slate'' unveiled a redesigned website. It introduced ''Slate V'' in 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slatev.com/ |title= Home |work= Slate V |accessdate= April 28, 2013}}</ref> an online video magazine with content that relates to or expands upon their written articles. In 2013, the magazine was redesigned under the guidance of Design Director [[Vivian Selbo]].\n\n''Slate'' was nominated for four digital [[National Magazine Awards]] in 2011 and won the [[American society of magazine editors#National Magazine Awards|NMA]] for General Excellence. In the same year, the magazine laid off several high-profile journalists, including co-founder [[Jack Shafer]] and [[Timothy Noah]] (author of the ''Chatterbox'' column).<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news |title= Slate magazine lays off Jack Shafer, Timothy Noah |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/slate-magazine-lays-off-jack-shafer-timothy-noah/2011/08/24/gIQAtCCgcJ_story.html |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= August 24, 2011 |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |issn= 0190-8286 |language= en|last= Farhi |first= Paul}}</ref> At the time, it had around 40 full-time editorial staff.<ref name=\":6\" /> The following year, a dedicated ad sales team was created.<ref>{{cite news|title= 'Slate' Gets a New Publisher |url= http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/slate-gets-new-publisher-143124 |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |work= [[Adweek]] |date= August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'' launched the \"Slate Book Review\" in 2012, a monthly books section edited by Dan Kois.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/business/media/slate-to-begin-a-monthly-review-of-books.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130227193805/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/business/media/slate-to-begin-a-monthly-review-of-books.html |archivedate= February 27, 2013 |title= Slate to Begin a Monthly Review of Books |date= March 1, 2012 |last= Bosman |first= Julie |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= April 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next year, ''Slate'' became profitable after preceding years had seen layoffs and falling ad revenues.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2014, ''Slate'' introduced a [[paywall system]] called \"Slate Plus\", offering ad-free podcasts and bonus materials. A year later, it had attracted 9,000 subscribers generating about $500,000 in annual revenue.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n''Slate'' moved all content behind a [[metered paywall]] for international readers in June 2015, explaining \"our U.S.-based sales team sells primarily to domestic advertisers, many of whom only want to reach a domestic audience. ...The end result is that, outside the United States, we are not covering our costs.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= Hello, International Reader|url= http://www.slate.com/articles/briefing/slate_fare/2015/06/slate_s_new_international_paywall_how_it_will_work_for_readers_abroad.html |work= Slate |date= June 7, 2015 |accessdate= June 7, 2015 |issn= 1091-2339 |last= Turner |first= Julia}}</ref> At the same time, it was stated that there were no plans for a domestic paywall.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSlate's articles have presented news and opinions from a liberal perspective, eventually evolving into a self-proclaimed liberal news site.\n\n=== Reputation for counterintuitive arguments (\"Slate pitches\") ===\nSince 2006,<ref name=\":1\" /> ''Slate'' has been known for publishing [[contrarian]] pieces arguing against commonly held views about a subject, giving rise to the #slatepitches Twitter [[hashtag]] in 2009.<ref name=\":2\" /> The ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'' has defined ''Slate'' [[Sales Pitch|pitches]] as \"an idea that sounds wrong or counterintuitive proposed as though it were the tightest logic ever,\" and in explaining its success wrote \"Readers want to click on Slate Pitches because they want to know what a writer could possibly say that would support their logic\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.cjr.org/the_kicker/trolling_readers.php |title= Stop trolling your readers|date= October 16, 2014 |access-date= October 16, 2014 |magazine= [[Columbia Journalism Review]] |last= Goldenberg |first= Kira}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''Slate''{{'}}s then editor-in-chief Julia Turner acknowledged a reputation for counterintuitive arguments forms part of ''Slate''<nowiki/>'s \"distinctive\" brand, but argued that the hashtag misrepresents the site's journalism. \"We are not looking to argue that up is down and black is white for the sake of being contrarian against all logic or intellectual rigor. But journalism is more interesting when it surprises you either with the conclusions that it reaches or the ways that it reaches them.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn a 2019 article for the site, ''Slate'' contributor Daniel Engber reflected on the changes that had occurred on the site since he started writing for it 15 years previously.  He suggested that its original worldview, influenced by its founder Kinsley and described by Engber as \"feisty, surprising, debate-club centrist-by-default\" and \"liberal contrarianism\", had shifted towards \"a more reliable, left-wing slant\", whilst still giving space for heterodox opinions, albeit \"tempered by other, graver duties\". He argued that this was necessary within the context of a \"Manichean age of flagrant cruelty and corruption\", although he also acknowledged that it could be \"a troubling limitation\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://slate.com/technology/2019/01/quillette-claire-lehmann-intellectual-dark-web.html |title=Free Thought for the Closed-Minded |last=Engber |first=Daniel |date=8 January 2019 |website=Slate (magazine) |access-date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Podcasts==\n{{see also|Panoply Media}}\n\nAccording to NiemanLab, ''Slate'' has been involved in [[podcast]]s \"almost from the very beginning\" of the medium.<ref name=\"NJLab\" /> Its first podcast offering, released on July 15, 2005,<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate's Podcasting Guide |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/podcasts/2005/07/slates_podcasting_guide.html |website= Slate|accessdate= August 3, 2012}}</ref> featured selected stories from the site read by Andy Bowers, who had joined ''Slate'' after leaving [[NPR]] in 2003.<ref name=\"NJLab\">{{cite web |website= [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|title=Slate doubles down on podcasts, courting niche audiences and happy advertisers |url= http://www.niemanlab.org/2012/06/slate-doubles-down-on-podcasts-courting-niche-audiences-and-happy-advertisers/ |last= Phelps |first= Andrew |date= June 4, 2012 |accessdate= April 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |url= http://www.niemanlab.org/2015/02/slates-podcast-audience-has-tripled-in-a-year-and-its-bet-on-audio-over-video-continues-to-pay-off/ |title= Slate\u2019s podcast audience has tripled in a year, and its bet on audio over video continues to pay off |last= Owens |first= Simon |date= February 6, 2015 |work= [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|NiemanLab]] |accessdate= February 6, 2015}}</ref> By June 2012, ''Slate'' had expanded their lineup to 19 podcasts, with ''Political Gabfest'' and ''Culture Gabfest'' being the most popular.<ref name=\"NJLab\" /> This count had shrunk to 14 by February 2015, with all receiving six million downloads per month.<ref name=\":3\" /> The podcasts are \"a profitable part of [''Slate'''s] business\"; the magazine charges more for advertising in its podcasts than in any of its other content.<ref name=\"NJLab\" />\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* ''Amicus'' \u2013 legal commentary\n* ''Audio Book Club''\n* ''Culture Gabfest''\n* ''Daily Podcast'' \u2013 some of everything\n* ''The Waves'' (formerly ''DoubleX'') \u2013 women's issues\n* ''Hang Up and Listen'' \u2013 sports\n* ''Hit Parade'' - pop music history\n* ''If Then'' - technology, Silicon Valley, and tech policy\n* ''Lexicon Valley'' \u2013 language issues\n* ''Manners for the Digital Age''\n* ''Mom and Dad Are Fighting'' \u2013 parenting\n* ''Money'' - business and finance\n* ''[[Slate Political Gabfest|Political Gabfest]]''\n* ''Spoiler Specials'' \u2013 film discussion\n* ''[[Studio 360]]'' - pop culture and the arts, in partnership with [[Public Radio International]]\n* ''[[The Gist]]''\n* [[Thirst Aid Kit]]\n* [[Slow Burn (podcast)|Slow Burn]]\n* ''Video Podcast''\n* ''Trumpcast''\n{{div col end}}\n\n''Slate'' podcasts have gotten longer over the years. The original ''Gabfest'' ran 15 minutes; by 2012, most ran about 45 minutes.<ref name=\"NJLab\" />\n\n==Staff==\n[[Jacob Weisberg]] was ''Slate's'' editor from 2002 until his designation as the chairman and editor-in-chief of The Slate Group in 2008. Weisberg's deputy editor [[David Plotz]] then became editor until July 2014,<ref name=\"slate2008\">{{cite magazine |last= Plotz |first= David  |title= David Plotz Says Goodbye |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/slate_fare/2014/07/slate_editor_david_plotz_julia_turner_succeeds_him_as_editor.html |magazine= Slate |date= July 14, 2014 |accessdate= July 14, 2014}}</ref> when he was replaced by [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]].\n\nTurner resigned as editor of ''Slate'' in October 2018.<ref name=\"turnerexit\">\n{{cite magazine\n| url=https://slate.com/briefing/2018/10/julia-turner-slate-goodbye-to-editor-in-chief.html\n| title=A Toast to Julia Turner\n| magazine=Slate\n| access-date=18 February 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Jared Hohlt]] became editor-in-chief on April 1, 2019.<ref name=\"PeiserEditor\">{{cite news |last1=Peiser |first1=Jaclyn |title=Slate Picks a Skilled Storyteller as Its New Top Editor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/06/business/media/slate-jared-hohlt.html?smid=tw-nytmedia&smtyp=cur |accessdate=7 March 2019 |newspaper=New York Times |date=6 March 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe Washington Post Company's John Alderman is ''Slate''{{'}}s publisher.\n\n===Key executives===\n* Lowen Liu (Deputy Editor)\n* [[Josh Levin]] (Editorial Director)\n* Allison Benedikt (Executive Editor)\n* Laura Bennett (Features Director)\n* Forrest Wickman (Culture Editor)\n* Charlie Kammerer (Chief Revenue Officer)\n\n===Notable contributors and departments===\n{{div col|colwidth=23em}}\n* [[Anne Applebaum]] (Foreigners)\n* [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] (Politics)\n* [[Simon Doonan]] (Fashion)\n* [[Stefan Fatsis]] (Hang Up and Listen)\n* [[Ashley Feinberg]] (Politics)\n* [[Daniel Gross]] (The Juice)\n* [[Fred Kaplan (journalist)|Fred Kaplan]] (War Stories)\n* [[Juliet Lapidos]] (Books / Explainer / Brow Beat)\n* [[Dahlia Lithwick]] (Jurisprudence)\n* [[Michael Moran (journalist)|Michael Moran]] (Reckoning / Foreign Policy)\n* [[Timothy Noah]] (The Customer)\n* [[Meghan O'Rourke]] (The Highbrow / Grieving)\n* [[Daniel Mallory Ortberg]] ([[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]], since 2015<ref name=yoffe2015>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/dear_prudence/2015/11/dear_prudence_emily_yoffe_says_goodbye.html|title=Don\u2019t Call It Closure|last=Yoffe|first=Emily|date=2015-11-12|newspaper=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref>)\n* [[Mike Pesca]] (The Gist)\n* [[Robert Pinsky]] (Poetry editor)\n* [[Phil Plait]] (Bad Astronomy / Science)\n* [[Ron Rosenbaum]] (Spectator)\n* [[William Saletan]] (Human Nature)\n* [[Jack Shafer]] (Press Box)\n* [[Eliot Spitzer]] (The Best Policy)\n* [[Michael Steinberger|Mike Steinberger]] (Drink)\n* [[Dana Stevens (critic)|Dana Stevens]] (Surfergirl through 2005/Movies)\n* [[Seth Stevenson]] (Ad Report Card / Well-Traveled)\n* [[James Surowiecki]] (The Book Club)\n* [[Leon Neyfakh]] (Podcast)\n* [[Tom Vanderbilt]] (Transport)\n* [[Jacob Weisberg]] (The Big Idea)\n* [[Tim Wu]] (Technology/Jurisprudence)\n* [[Emily Yoffe]] ([[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]] - until 2015 -, Human Guinea-pig)<ref name=yoffe2015/>\n* [[Reihan Salam]] (Politics)\n* [[Laura Miller (writer)|Laura Miller]] (Books and Culture)\n* [[Carl Wilson (writer)|Carl Wilson]] (Music)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Past contributors===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Emily Bazelon]]\n* [[Ian Bremmer]]\n* [[Phil Carter]]\n* [[David Edelstein]]\n* [[Franklin Foer]]\n* [[Sasha Frere-Jones]]\n* [[Atul Gawande]]\n* [[Austan Goolsbee]]\n* [[Robert Lane Greene]]\n* [[Virginia Heffernan]]\n* [[David Helvarg]]\n* [[Christopher Hitchens]]\n* [[Mickey Kaus]]\n* [[Paul Krugman]]\n* [[Steven Landsburg]]\n* [[Will Leitch]]\n* [[Farhad Manjoo]]\n* [[Louis Menand]]\n* [[David Plotz]]\n* [[Daniel Radosh]]\n* [[Bruce Reed (political operative)|Bruce Reed]]\n* [[Jody Rosen]]\n* [[Herbert Stein]]\n* [[James Surowiecki]]\n* [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]]\n* [[Rob Walker (journalist)|Rob Walker]]\n* [[David Weigel]]\n* [[Robert Wright (journalist)|Robert Wright]]\n* [[Matthew Yglesias]]\n* [[Fareed Zakaria]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Other recurring features==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Assessment\n* Books\n* Dear Prudence (advice column)\n* Dispatches\n* Drink\n* Food\n* Foreigners\n* Gaming\n* Science Denial\n* Shopping\n* The Good Word (language)\n* The Movie Club\n* The TV Club\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Blogs===\n* ''Behold'', ''Slate'''s photo blog\n* ''Brow Beat'', ''Slate'''s culture blog\n* ''Crime'', a crime blog\n* ''Future Tense'', a technology blog produced as part of a partnership between Slate, the [[New America Foundation]], and [[Arizona State University]]\n* ''Lexicon Valley'', a blog about language\n* ''Moneybox'', ''Slate'''s business and economics blog\n* ''Outward'', ''Slate'''s [[LGBTQ]] blog\n* ''The Eye'', a design blog\n* ''The Vault'', ''Slate'''s history blog\n* ''The World'', a blog about [[foreign affairs]]\n* ''Wild Things'', ''Slate'''s animals blog\n* ''XX Factor'', a blog about women's issues. In 2009, it gave rise to ''Double X'', launched by The Slate Group as a separate online magazine about women's topics, edited by [[Hanna Rosin]] and [[Emily Bazelon]], which was folded back into a Slate.com section after half a year.<ref>{{cite news |title= Double X Is Folded Into Slate Magazine |url= http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/16/double-x-is-folded-into-slate-magazine/ |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |last= Stelter |first= Brian |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= November 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Summary columns===\n* [[Slatest]] ([[news aggregator]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Slate (magazine)}}\n* {{official website|https://slate.com}}\n* [https://www.slate.fr/ ''Slate''] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Graham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slate (magazine)}}\n[[Category:American online magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1996]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:American cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:American political websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|U.S.-based online magazine}}\n{{Italic title}}\n{{Use American English|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox website\n| logo = Slate new logo.svg\n| screenshot = Slate homepage 2013-11-09.png\n| collapsible =\n| collapsetext =\n| caption =\n| url = {{url|https://slate.com}}, {{url|https://slate.fr}}\n| commercial = Yes\n| type = Online magazine\n| registration = Optional for Slate Plus and commenting only (US readers)<br />\nMetered paywall (non-US readers)\n| language =\n| num_users =\n| content_license =\n| owner = [[The Slate Group]]\n| editor = [[Jared Hohlt]]\n| author = [[Michael Kinsley]]\n| launch_date = {{start date and age|1996}}\n| revenue =\n| alexa = {{Decrease}} 2,374 ({{as of|2020|1|3|alt=December 2019}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |url= http://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/slate.com |title= Slate.com Site Info |publisher= [[Alexa Internet]] |access-date= January 3, 2020}}</ref>\n| political = \n| issn = 1090-6584\n| eissn = 1091-2339\n| oclc = 728292344\n| current_status = Active\n| footnotes =\n| name = ''Slate''\n| logocaption =\n}}\n'''''Slate''''' is an online magazine that covers current affairs, politics, and culture in the United States. It is known, and sometimes criticized, for adopting [[contrarian]] views, giving rise to the term \"Slate Pitches\".<ref>{{cite news |title= Contrarianism's end? |url=https://www.economist.com/blogs/democracyinamerica/2009/10/contrarianisms_end_1 |newspaper= [[The Economist]] |date= October 19, 2009}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite magazine |last= Weisberg |first= Jacob |title= What Makes Slate Slatey? |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/slates_10th_anniversary/2006/06/what_makes_slate_slatey.single.html |magazine= Slate |date= June 19, 2006 |quote= To be a Slatey writer, you must cut through the media welter [...] This can be done in a number of ways. [One] is to make the contrarian case that all the common assumptions about a subject are simply and hopelessly wrong.}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite news |last= Coscarelli |first= Joe |title= Slate\u2019s Contrarian Ways Mocked On Twitter|url=http://www.mediaite.com/online/slates-contrarian-ways-mocked-on-twitter/ |publisher= [[Mediaite]] |date= October 23, 2009}}</ref> It has a generally [[Modern liberalism in the United States|liberal]] editorial stance.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2014/10/21/lets-rank-the-media-from-liberal-to-conservative-based-on-their-audiences/|title=Ranking the media from liberal to conservative, based on their audiences|first=Aaron|last=Blake|date=October 21, 2014|website=Washington Post|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2005/06/wolff200506|title=No Jokes, Please, We're Liberal|first=Michael|last=Wolff|date=|website=VanityFair.com|access-date=August 31, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Winter|first1=Jessica|title=Slate Isn\u2019t Too Liberal. But\u2026|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/slate_plus/slate_fare/2014/09/is_slate_magazine_too_liberal_or_conservative_what_members_said_about_the.html|website=Slate|accessdate=21 September 2017|date=21 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nIt was created in 1996 by former ''[[The New Republic|New Republic]]'' editor [[Michael Kinsley]], initially under the ownership of [[Microsoft]] as part of [[MSN]]. In 2004, it was purchased by [[Graham Holdings|The Washington Post Company]] (later renamed the Graham Holdings Company), and since 2008 has been managed by [[The Slate Group]], an online publishing entity created by Graham Holdings. ''Slate'' is based in New York City, with an additional office in Washington, D.C.<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate Magazine: Private Company Information - Businessweek |url= https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapId=8200230 |publisher= Bloomberg.com |access-date= July 2, 2015}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'', which is updated throughout the day, covers politics, arts and culture, sports, and news. According to its former editor-in-chief [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]], the magazine is \"not fundamentally a breaking news source\", but rather aimed at helping readers to \"analyze and understand and interpret the world\" with witty and entertaining writing.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news |url= http://www.capitalnewyork.com/article/media/2014/09/8553356/long-serving-deputy-julia-turner-takes-reins-slate |title= Long-serving deputy Julia Turner takes the reins at Slate |last= Levy |first= Nicole |date= September 30, 2014 |work= [[Politico|Capital New York]] |access-date= September 30, 2014}}</ref> As of mid-2015, it publishes about 1,500 stories per month.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web |title= Unlimited FAQ |url= https://secure.slate.com/unlimited |work= Slate |access-date= July 2, 2015 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150703071551/https://secure.slate.com/unlimited |archive-date= July 3, 2015 |url-status= dead |df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\nA French version, ''slate.fr'', was launched in February 2009 by a group of four journalists, including [[Jean-Marie Colombani]], Eric Leser, and economist [[Jacques Attali]]. Among them, the founders hold 50 percent in the publishing company, while The Slate Group holds 15 percent.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.cbsnews.com/stories/2009/02/15/paidcontent/main4803947.shtml |work= [[CBS News]] |title= Interview: Jacob Weisberg, Chairman, Slate Group: Breaking Out of the Beltway |date= February 15, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.lepoint.fr/actualites-technologie-internet/2009-02-11/slate-fr-jean-marie-colombani-a-l-assaut-du-web/1387/0/315818 |title= Slate.fr: Jean-Marie Colombani \u00e0 l'assaut du Web, actualit\u00e9 Tech & Net \u2013 Le Point |magazine= [[Le Point]] |date= February 10, 2009 |access-date= April 28, 2013| language= French}}</ref> In 2011, ''slate.fr'' started a separate site covering African news, ''Slate Afrique'', with a Paris-based editorial staff.<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate Afrique |url= http://www.voxeurop.eu/en/content/source-profile/2135951-slate-afrique |access-date= July 2, 2015 |publisher= VoxEurop |date= June 20, 2012}}</ref>\n\nIt is ad-supported and has been available to read free of charge since 1999, but restricted access for non-US readers via a [[metered paywall]] in 2015.\n\n==Background==\n''Slate'' features regular and semi-regular columns such as ''Explainer, Moneybox, Spectator, Transport'', and ''[[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]]''. Many of the articles are short (less than 2,000 words) and argument-driven. Around 2010, the magazine also began running long-form journalism. Many of the longer stories are an outgrowth of the \"Fresca Fellowships\", so-called because former editor Plotz liked the soft drink [[Fresca]]. \"The idea is that every writer and editor on staff has to spend a month or six weeks a year not doing their regular job, but instead working on a long, ambitious project of some sort,\" Plotz said in an interview.<ref>{{cite web |last=Levy |first=Dan |date= April 4, 2011 |title=Slate of Mind: Q&A with David Plotz |url= http://sparksheet.com/slate-of-mind-qa-with-david-plotz/ |work=Sparksheet |accessdate=3 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'' introduced a [[paywall]]-based business model in 1998 that attracted up 20,000 subscribers but was later abandoned.<ref name=\":5\">{{cite news |last= Sawers |first= Paul |date= June 8, 2015 |title= Slate slides behind a metered paywall as global readers are asked to pay $5/month|url= https://venturebeat.com/2015/06/08/slate-slides-behind-a-paywall-as-global-readers-are-asked-to-pay-5month-to-read-more-than-5-articles/ |work=[[VentureBeat]] |accessdate= July 2, 2015}}</ref> A similar subscription model was implemented in April 2001 by ''Slate''{{'}}s independently owned competitor, [[Salon.com]].\n\n''Slate'' started a daily feature, \"Today's Pictures\", on November 30, 2005, which featured 15\u201320 photographs from the archive at [[Magnum Photos]] that share a common theme. The column also features two [[Flash animation|Flash animated]] \"Interactive Essays\" a month.\n\n[[File:Slate screenshot.png|thumb|right|The design of ''Slate''{{'}}s homepage from 2006 to 2013]]\n\nOn its 10th anniversary, ''Slate'' unveiled a redesigned website. It introduced ''Slate V'' in 2007,<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.slatev.com/ |title= Home |work= Slate V |accessdate= April 28, 2013}}</ref> an online video magazine with content that relates to or expands upon their written articles. In 2013, the magazine was redesigned under the guidance of Design Director [[Vivian Selbo]].\n\n''Slate'' was nominated for four digital [[National Magazine Awards]] in 2011 and won the [[American society of magazine editors#National Magazine Awards|NMA]] for General Excellence. In the same year, the magazine laid off several high-profile journalists, including co-founder [[Jack Shafer]] and [[Timothy Noah]] (author of the ''Chatterbox'' column).<ref name=\":6\">{{cite news |title= Slate magazine lays off Jack Shafer, Timothy Noah |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/slate-magazine-lays-off-jack-shafer-timothy-noah/2011/08/24/gIQAtCCgcJ_story.html |newspaper= [[The Washington Post]] |date= August 24, 2011 |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |issn= 0190-8286 |language= en|last= Farhi |first= Paul}}</ref> At the time, it had around 40 full-time editorial staff.<ref name=\":6\" /> The following year, a dedicated ad sales team was created.<ref>{{cite news|title= 'Slate' Gets a New Publisher |url= http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/slate-gets-new-publisher-143124 |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |work= [[Adweek]] |date= August 27, 2012}}</ref>\n\n''Slate'' launched the \"Slate Book Review\" in 2012, a monthly books section edited by Dan Kois.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/business/media/slate-to-begin-a-monthly-review-of-books.html |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130227193805/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/02/business/media/slate-to-begin-a-monthly-review-of-books.html |archivedate= February 27, 2013 |title= Slate to Begin a Monthly Review of Books |date= March 1, 2012 |last= Bosman |first= Julie |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |access-date= April 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe next year, ''Slate'' became profitable after preceding years had seen layoffs and falling ad revenues.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2014, ''Slate'' introduced a [[paywall system]] called \"Slate Plus\", offering ad-free podcasts and bonus materials. A year later, it had attracted 9,000 subscribers generating about $500,000 in annual revenue.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n''Slate'' moved all content behind a [[metered paywall]] for international readers in June 2015, explaining \"our U.S.-based sales team sells primarily to domestic advertisers, many of whom only want to reach a domestic audience. ...The end result is that, outside the United States, we are not covering our costs.\"<ref>{{cite news |title= Hello, International Reader|url= http://www.slate.com/articles/briefing/slate_fare/2015/06/slate_s_new_international_paywall_how_it_will_work_for_readers_abroad.html |work= Slate |date= June 7, 2015 |accessdate= June 7, 2015 |issn= 1091-2339 |last= Turner |first= Julia}}</ref> At the same time, it was stated that there were no plans for a domestic paywall.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nSlate's articles have presented news and opinions from a liberal perspective, eventually evolving into a self-proclaimed liberal news site.\n\n=== Reputation for counterintuitive arguments (\"Slate pitches\") ===\nSince 2006,<ref name=\":1\" /> ''Slate'' has been known for publishing [[contrarian]] pieces arguing against commonly held views about a subject, giving rise to the #slatepitches Twitter [[hashtag]] in 2009.<ref name=\":2\" /> The ''[[Columbia Journalism Review]]'' has defined ''Slate'' [[Sales Pitch|pitches]] as \"an idea that sounds wrong or counterintuitive proposed as though it were the tightest logic ever,\" and in explaining its success wrote \"Readers want to click on Slate Pitches because they want to know what a writer could possibly say that would support their logic\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url= http://www.cjr.org/the_kicker/trolling_readers.php |title= Stop trolling your readers|date= October 16, 2014 |access-date= October 16, 2014 |magazine= [[Columbia Journalism Review]] |last= Goldenberg |first= Kira}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, ''Slate''{{'}}s then editor-in-chief Julia Turner acknowledged a reputation for counterintuitive arguments forms part of ''Slate''<nowiki/>'s \"distinctive\" brand, but argued that the hashtag misrepresents the site's journalism. \"We are not looking to argue that up is down and black is white for the sake of being contrarian against all logic or intellectual rigor. But journalism is more interesting when it surprises you either with the conclusions that it reaches or the ways that it reaches them.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn a 2019 article for the site, ''Slate'' contributor Daniel Engber reflected on the changes that had occurred on the site since he started writing for it 15 years previously.  He suggested that its original worldview, influenced by its founder Kinsley and described by Engber as \"feisty, surprising, debate-club centrist-by-default\" and \"liberal contrarianism\", had shifted towards \"a more reliable, left-wing slant\", whilst still giving space for heterodox opinions, albeit \"tempered by other, graver duties\". He argued that this was necessary within the context of a \"Manichean age of flagrant cruelty and corruption\", although he also acknowledged that it could be \"a troubling limitation\".<ref>{{cite web |url=https://slate.com/technology/2019/01/quillette-claire-lehmann-intellectual-dark-web.html |title=Free Thought for the Closed-Minded |last=Engber |first=Daniel |date=8 January 2019 |website=Slate (magazine) |access-date=9 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Podcasts==\n{{see also|Panoply Media}}\n\nAccording to NiemanLab, ''Slate'' has been involved in [[podcast]]s \"almost from the very beginning\" of the medium.<ref name=\"NJLab\" /> Its first podcast offering, released on July 15, 2005,<ref>{{cite web |title= Slate's Podcasting Guide |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/podcasts/podcasts/2005/07/slates_podcasting_guide.html |website= Slate|accessdate= August 3, 2012}}</ref> featured selected stories from the site read by Andy Bowers, who had joined ''Slate'' after leaving [[NPR]] in 2003.<ref name=\"NJLab\">{{cite web |website= [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism]]|title=Slate doubles down on podcasts, courting niche audiences and happy advertisers |url= http://www.niemanlab.org/2012/06/slate-doubles-down-on-podcasts-courting-niche-audiences-and-happy-advertisers/ |last= Phelps |first= Andrew |date= June 4, 2012 |accessdate= April 28, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news |url= http://www.niemanlab.org/2015/02/slates-podcast-audience-has-tripled-in-a-year-and-its-bet-on-audio-over-video-continues-to-pay-off/ |title= Slate\u2019s podcast audience has tripled in a year, and its bet on audio over video continues to pay off |last= Owens |first= Simon |date= February 6, 2015 |work= [[Nieman Foundation for Journalism|NiemanLab]] |accessdate= February 6, 2015}}</ref> By June 2012, ''Slate'' had expanded their lineup to 19 podcasts, with ''Political Gabfest'' and ''Culture Gabfest'' being the most popular.<ref name=\"NJLab\" /> This count had shrunk to 14 by February 2015, with all receiving six million downloads per month.<ref name=\":3\" /> The podcasts are \"a profitable part of [''Slate'''s] business\"; the magazine charges more for advertising in its podcasts than in any of its other content.<ref name=\"NJLab\" />\n\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* ''Amicus'' \u2013 legal commentary\n* ''Audio Book Club''\n* ''Culture Gabfest''\n* ''Daily Podcast'' \u2013 some of everything\n* ''The Waves'' (formerly ''DoubleX'') \u2013 women's issues\n* ''Hang Up and Listen'' \u2013 sports\n* ''Hit Parade'' - pop music history\n* ''If Then'' - technology, Silicon Valley, and tech policy\n* ''Lexicon Valley'' \u2013 language issues\n* ''Manners for the Digital Age''\n* ''Mom and Dad Are Fighting'' \u2013 parenting\n* ''Money'' - business and finance\n* ''[[Slate Political Gabfest|Political Gabfest]]''\n* ''Spoiler Specials'' \u2013 film discussion\n* ''[[Studio 360]]'' - pop culture and the arts, in partnership with [[Public Radio International]]\n* ''[[The Gist]]''\n* [[Thirst Aid Kit]]\n* [[Slow Burn (podcast)|Slow Burn]]\n* ''Video Podcast''\n* ''Trumpcast''\n{{div col end}}\n\n''Slate'' podcasts have gotten longer over the years. The original ''Gabfest'' ran 15 minutes; by 2012, most ran about 45 minutes.<ref name=\"NJLab\" />\n\n==Staff==\n[[Jacob Weisberg]] was ''Slate's'' editor from 2002 until his designation as the chairman and editor-in-chief of The Slate Group in 2008. Weisberg's deputy editor [[David Plotz]] then became editor until July 2014<ref name=\"slate2008\">{{cite magazine |last= Plotz |first= David  |title= David Plotz Says Goodbye |url= http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/slate_fare/2014/07/slate_editor_david_plotz_julia_turner_succeeds_him_as_editor.html |magazine= Slate |date= July 14, 2014 |accessdate= July 14, 2014}}</ref>, when he was replaced by [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]].\n\nTurner resigned as editor of ''Slate'' in October 2018.<ref name=\"turnerexit\">\n{{cite magazine\n| url=https://slate.com/briefing/2018/10/julia-turner-slate-goodbye-to-editor-in-chief.html\n| title=A Toast to Julia Turner\n| magazine=Slate\n| access-date=18 February 2019\n}}</ref>\n\n[[Jared Hohlt]] became editor-in-chief on April 1, 2019.<ref name=\"PeiserEditor\">{{cite news |last1=Peiser |first1=Jaclyn |title=Slate Picks a Skilled Storyteller as Its New Top Editor |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/06/business/media/slate-jared-hohlt.html?smid=tw-nytmedia&smtyp=cur |accessdate=7 March 2019 |newspaper=New York Times |date=6 March 2019}}</ref> \n\nThe Washington Post Company's John Alderman is ''Slate''{{'}}s publisher.\n\n===Key executives===\n* Lowen Liu (Deputy Editor)\n* [[Josh Levin]] (Editorial Director)\n* Allison Benedikt (Executive Editor)\n* Laura Bennett (Features Director)\n* Forrest Wickman (Culture Editor)\n* Charlie Kammerer (Chief Revenue Officer)\n\n===Notable contributors and departments===\n{{div col|colwidth=23em}}\n* [[Anne Applebaum]] (Foreigners)\n* [[John Dickerson (journalist)|John Dickerson]] (Politics)\n* [[Simon Doonan]] (Fashion)\n* [[Stefan Fatsis]] (Hang Up and Listen)\n* [[Ashley Feinberg]] (Politics)\n* [[Daniel Gross]] (The Juice)\n* [[Fred Kaplan (journalist)|Fred Kaplan]] (War Stories)\n* [[Juliet Lapidos]] (Books / Explainer / Brow Beat)\n* [[Dahlia Lithwick]] (Jurisprudence)\n* [[Michael Moran (journalist)|Michael Moran]] (Reckoning / Foreign Policy)\n* [[Timothy Noah]] (The Customer)\n* [[Meghan O'Rourke]] (The Highbrow / Grieving)\n* [[Daniel Mallory Ortberg]] ([[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]], since 2015<ref name=yoffe2015>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/life/dear_prudence/2015/11/dear_prudence_emily_yoffe_says_goodbye.html|title=Don\u2019t Call It Closure|last=Yoffe|first=Emily|date=2015-11-12|newspaper=Slate|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|access-date=2016-07-31}}</ref>)\n* [[Mike Pesca]] (The Gist)\n* [[Robert Pinsky]] (Poetry editor)\n* [[Phil Plait]] (Bad Astronomy / Science)\n* [[Ron Rosenbaum]] (Spectator)\n* [[William Saletan]] (Human Nature)\n* [[Jack Shafer]] (Press Box)\n* [[Eliot Spitzer]] (The Best Policy)\n* [[Michael Steinberger|Mike Steinberger]] (Drink)\n* [[Dana Stevens (critic)|Dana Stevens]] (Surfergirl through 2005/Movies)\n* [[Seth Stevenson]] (Ad Report Card / Well-Traveled)\n* [[James Surowiecki]] (The Book Club)\n* [[Leon Neyfakh]] (Podcast)\n* [[Tom Vanderbilt]] (Transport)\n* [[Jacob Weisberg]] (The Big Idea)\n* [[Tim Wu]] (Technology/Jurisprudence)\n* [[Emily Yoffe]] ([[Dear Prudence (advice column)|Dear Prudence]] - until 2015 -, Human Guinea-pig)<ref name=yoffe2015/>\n* [[Reihan Salam]] (Politics)\n* [[Laura Miller (writer)|Laura Miller]] (Books and Culture)\n* [[Carl Wilson (writer)|Carl Wilson]] (Music)\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Past contributors===\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Emily Bazelon]]\n* [[Ian Bremmer]]\n* [[Phil Carter]]\n* [[David Edelstein]]\n* [[Franklin Foer]]\n* [[Sasha Frere-Jones]]\n* [[Atul Gawande]]\n* [[Austan Goolsbee]]\n* [[Robert Lane Greene]]\n* [[Virginia Heffernan]]\n* [[David Helvarg]]\n* [[Christopher Hitchens]]\n* [[Mickey Kaus]]\n* [[Paul Krugman]]\n* [[Steven Landsburg]]\n* [[Will Leitch]]\n* [[Farhad Manjoo]]\n* [[Louis Menand]]\n* [[David Plotz]]\n* [[Daniel Radosh]]\n* [[Bruce Reed (political operative)|Bruce Reed]]\n* [[Jody Rosen]]\n* [[Herbert Stein]]\n* [[James Surowiecki]]\n* [[Julia Turner (journalist)|Julia Turner]]\n* [[Rob Walker (journalist)|Rob Walker]]\n* [[David Weigel]]\n* [[Robert Wright (journalist)|Robert Wright]]\n* [[Matthew Yglesias]]\n* [[Fareed Zakaria]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Other recurring features==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* Assessment\n* Books\n* Dear Prudence (advice column)\n* Dispatches\n* Drink\n* Food\n* Foreigners\n* Gaming\n* Science Denial\n* Shopping\n* The Good Word (language)\n* The Movie Club\n* The TV Club\n{{div col end}}\n\n===Blogs===\n* ''Behold'', ''Slate'''s photo blog\n* ''Brow Beat'', ''Slate'''s culture blog\n* ''Crime'', a crime blog\n* ''Future Tense'', a technology blog produced as part of a partnership between Slate, the [[New America Foundation]], and [[Arizona State University]]\n* ''Lexicon Valley'', a blog about language\n* ''Moneybox'', ''Slate'''s business and economics blog\n* ''Outward'', ''Slate'''s [[LGBTQ]] blog\n* ''The Eye'', a design blog\n* ''The Vault'', ''Slate'''s history blog\n* ''The World'', a blog about [[foreign affairs]]\n* ''Wild Things'', ''Slate'''s animals blog\n* ''XX Factor'', a blog about women's issues. In 2009, it gave rise to ''Double X'', launched by The Slate Group as a separate online magazine about women's topics, edited by [[Hanna Rosin]] and [[Emily Bazelon]], which was folded back into a Slate.com section after half a year.<ref>{{cite news |title= Double X Is Folded Into Slate Magazine |url= http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/16/double-x-is-folded-into-slate-magazine/ |accessdate= July 12, 2015 |last= Stelter |first= Brian |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |date= November 16, 2009}}</ref>\n\n===Summary columns===\n* [[Slatest]] ([[news aggregator]])\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Slate (magazine)}}\n* {{official website|https://slate.com}}\n* [https://www.slate.fr/ ''Slate''] {{in lang|fr}}\n\n{{Graham}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Slate (magazine)}}\n[[Category:American online magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines established in 1996]]\n[[Category:American political magazines]]\n[[Category:Cultural magazines]]\n[[Category:Magazines published in New York City]]\n[[Category:American political websites]]\n", "name_user": "Hmains", "label": "safe", "comment": "category refine, sort sequence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slate_(magazine)"}
{"title_page": "Precious and Few", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Precious and Few\n| cover      = Precious_and_Few_-_Climax.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Climax (band)|Climax]]\n| album      = Climax Featuring Sonny Geraci\n| B-side     = Park Preserve\n| released   = December 1971\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1971\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]\n| length     = 2:43\n| label      = Carousel/Rocky Road Records\n| writer     = Walter D. Nims\n| producer   = Larry Cox\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Life and Breath\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n\"'''Precious and Few'''\" is a song recorded by American group [[Climax (band)|Climax]] which became a major North American hit in early 1972.  Written by the band's guitarist, Walter D. Nims, it spent three weeks at number three on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and hit number one on the ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100.<ref name=\"CB22672\">[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1972/Cash-Box-1972-02-26.pdf Cash Box Top 100], ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'', February 26, 1972. p. 4. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref> It also reached number six on Canada's ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' 100.<ref name=\"RPM100\">\"[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.7602.pdf RPM 100]\", ''RPM'',  Volume 17, No. 4, March 11, 1972. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref>\n\nLead vocals were provided by [[Sonny Geraci]], who also sang lead on \"[[Time Won't Let Me]]\" by his previous band, [[The Outsiders (American band)|The Outsiders]]. Nims had also been a member of The Outsiders.\n\n\"Precious and Few\" had originally been released on Carousel Records in 1971. The song featured [[The Ron Hicklin Singers]] as backing vocalists, a piano, drums, strings and a horn section.\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin|width=65%}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Chart (1971-72)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Australia ''[[Go-Set]]''<ref>[[Ed Nimmervoll]], \"[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1972/19720805.html Go-Set National Top 40]\", August 5, 1972. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| 29\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' 100<ref name=\"RPM100\"/>\n| 6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' [[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]] Playlist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.7722&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.7722.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.7722 |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n| 13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/299434/climax/chart Climax - Chart History - The Hot 100], ''Billboard.com''. Accessed November 16, 2016.</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/299434/climax/chart?f=341 Climax - Chart History - Adult Contemporary], ''Billboard.com''. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-03-04-I.pdf Billboard Top 40 Easy Listening]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', March 4, 1972. p. 46. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref name=\"CB22672\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Record World]]'' The Singles Chart<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/72/Record-World-1972-03-11.pdf The Singles Chart]\", ''[[Record World]]'', March 11, 1972. Retrieved April 15, 2018.</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Record World'' The M.O.R. Chart<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/72/Record-World-1972-03-04.pdf The M.O.R. Chart]\", ''[[Record World]]'', March 4, 1972. p. 21. Retrieved April 15, 2018.</ref>\n| 3\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1972)\n! Rank\n|-\n|Canada\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-12-30.pdf Top Pop 100 Singles]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', December 30, 1972. p. TA-20. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Easy Listening<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-12-30.pdf Top Easy Listening Singles]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', December 30, 1972. p. TA-22. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|48\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1972/Cash-Box-1972-12-30.pdf Top 100 Singles of 72]\", ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'', December 30, 1972. p. 36. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n*Filipino music group The Company covered the song, released in 1999.\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.songlyrics.com/climax/precious-and-few-lyrics/ Lyrics of this song]<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|SCFSj6w6PhI|Listen to \"Precious and Few\"}} \n\n[[Category:1971 songs]]\n[[Category:1971 debut singles]]\n[[Category:Climax (band) songs]]\n{{1970s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Precious and Few\n| cover      = Precious_and_Few_-_Climax.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Climax (band)|Climax]]\n| album      = Climax Featuring Sonny Geraci\n| B-side     = Park Preserve\n| released   = December 1971\n| format     = [[Gramophone record|7\"]]\n| recorded   = 1971\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Soft rock]]\n| length     = 2:43\n| label      = Carousel/Rocky Road Records\n| writer     = Walter D. Nims\n| producer   = Larry Cox\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Life and Breath\n| next_year  = 1972\n}}\n\n\"'''Precious and Few'''\" is a song recorded by American group [[Climax (band)|Climax]] which became a major North American hit in early 1972.  Written by the band's guitarist, Walter D. Nims, it spent three weeks at number three on the U.S. [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and hit number one on the ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100.<ref name=\"CB22672\">[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1972/Cash-Box-1972-02-26.pdf Cash Box Top 100], ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'', February 26, 1972. p. 4. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref> It also reached number six on Canada's ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' 100.<ref name=\"RPM100\">\"[http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/obj/028020/f2/nlc008388.7602.pdf RPM 100]\", ''RPM'',  Volume 17, No. 4, March 11, 1972. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref>\n\nLead vocals were provided by [[Sonny Geraci]], who also sang lead on \"[[Time Won't Let Me]]\" by his previous band, [[The Outsiders (American band)|The Outsiders]]. Nims had also been a member of The Outsiders.\n\n\"Precious and Few\" had originally been released on Carousel Records in 1971. The song featured [[The Ron Hicklin Singers]] as backing vocalists, a piano, drums, strings and a horn section.\n\n==Cover versions==\n*Filipino music group The Company covered the song, released in 1999.\n\n==Chart performance==\n{{col-begin|width=65%}}\n{{col-2}}\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Chart (1971-72)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"|Australia ''[[Go-Set]]''<ref>[[Ed Nimmervoll]], \"[http://www.poparchives.com.au/gosetcharts/1972/19720805.html Go-Set National Top 40]\", August 5, 1972. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| 29\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'' 100<ref name=\"RPM100\"/>\n| 6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canadian ''RPM'' [[Middle of the road (music)|MOR]] Playlist<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bac-lac.gc.ca/eng/discover/films-videos-sound-recordings/rpm/Pages/image.aspx?Image=nlc008388.7722&URLjpg=http%3a%2f%2fwww.collectionscanada.gc.ca%2fobj%2f028020%2ff4%2fnlc008388.7722.gif&Ecopy=nlc008388.7722 |title=Image : RPM Weekly - Library and Archives Canada |website=Bac-lac.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-05}}</ref>\n| 13\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Billboard Hot 100|Hot 100]]<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/299434/climax/chart Climax - Chart History - The Hot 100], ''Billboard.com''. Accessed November 16, 2016.</ref>\n| 3\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Adult Contemporary (chart)|Easy Listening]]<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/artist/299434/climax/chart?f=341 Climax - Chart History - Adult Contemporary], ''Billboard.com''. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref><ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-03-04-I.pdf Billboard Top 40 Easy Listening]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', March 4, 1972. p. 46. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| 6\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'' Top 100<ref name=\"CB22672\"/>\n| 1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''[[Record World]]'' The Singles Chart<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/72/Record-World-1972-03-11.pdf The Singles Chart]\", ''[[Record World]]'', March 11, 1972. Retrieved April 15, 2018.</ref>\n| 1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|U.S. ''Record World'' The M.O.R. Chart<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Record-World/70s/72/Record-World-1972-03-04.pdf The M.O.R. Chart]\", ''[[Record World]]'', March 4, 1972. p. 21. Retrieved April 15, 2018.</ref>\n| 3\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (1972)\n! Rank\n|-\n|Canada\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|28\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-12-30.pdf Top Pop 100 Singles]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', December 30, 1972. p. TA-20. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|30\n|-\n|U.S. ''Billboard'' Easy Listening<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Billboard/70s/1972/BB-1972-12-30.pdf Top Easy Listening Singles]\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'', December 30, 1972. p. TA-22. Retrieved November 22, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|48\n|-\n|U.S. ''Cash Box''<ref>\"[http://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-Cash-Box/70s/1972/Cash-Box-1972-12-30.pdf Top 100 Singles of 72]\", ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]'', December 30, 1972. p. 36. Retrieved November 16, 2016.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|31\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of one-hit wonders in the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.songlyrics.com/climax/precious-and-few-lyrics/ Lyrics of this song]<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* {{YouTube|SCFSj6w6PhI|Listen to \"Precious and Few\"}} \n\n[[Category:1971 songs]]\n[[Category:1971 debut singles]]\n[[Category:Climax (band) songs]]\n{{1970s-pop-song-stub}}\n", "name_user": "JGabbard", "label": "safe", "comment": "rearr.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Precious_and_Few"}
{"title_page": "41 Canadian Brigade Group", "text_new": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=41 Canadian Brigade Group\n|native_name={{nativename|fr|nolink=on|41<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}\n| image= 41CanadianBrigadeGroup.jpg\n|caption=41&nbsp;CBG badge\n|dates= 1 April 1997 \u2013 present\n|country=[[Canada]]\n|branch=[[Canadian Army]]\n|command_structure=[[3rd Canadian Division]]\n|type=[[Brigade group]]\n|identification_symbol_4=41&nbsp;CBG\n|identification_symbol_4_label=Abbreviation\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|ceremonial_chief_label=Colonel-in-Chief\n|nickname= \"Alberta's Brigade\"\n|march= \"[[Don Quixote (album)|Alberta Bound]]\"\n|motto= Fortune Favours the Bold\n|garrison=LGen Stan Waters Building, [[Calgary]]\n|website={{official URL}}\n<!--Command Team-->\n|commander1=Colonel Michael Vernon, C.D.\n|commander1_label=Commander\n|commander2=Lieutenant-Colonel Chris Hunt, C.D.\n|commander2_label=Deputy Commander\n|commander3=Chief Warrant Officer Scott Doyle, C,D,\n|commander3_label=Brigade Sergeant Major\n|notable_commanders=\n}}\n'''41 Canadian Brigade Group''' (41&nbsp;CBG; {{lang-fr|links=no|41<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}) is a [[Canadian Army]] formation of the [[3rd Canadian Division]]. The formation is composed of [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] units within the province of [[Alberta]]. The home station of the brigade is in [[Calgary]].\n\nThe brigade has an establishment of 2,500 all ranks.  The role of the [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] is to be \"a professional part-time force that provides local engagement and a responsive integrated capability, at home or abroad, in sustainment of the Army mission.\"  Most of the soldiers within the brigade serve part time in units or sub-units stationed in their communities.  As the [[Canadian Army]] generates task-specific units for employment on expeditionary and domestic operations under the command of the [[Canadian Joint Operations Command]], 41&nbsp;CBG, as a force generator, is tasked with the following:\n\n# On order provide general-purpose, combat-capable soldiers and specialist sub-subunits (troops or platoons) capable of augmenting the Regular Force on expeditionary operations; and\n# On order provide a domestic response unit (territorial battalion group) or subunits (squadrons or companies) capable of augmenting the Regular Force on domestic operations.\n\n==Corporate identity==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:41 CBG Camp Flag.png|Brigade camp flag\nFile:41 CBG Comd Pennant.jpg|Commander's pennant\nFile:41 CBG Logo.jpg|Brigade logo\nFile:41 CBG Brigade Tie.jpg|Brigade necktie\nFile:41 CBG Brand.jpg|Brigade brand\n</gallery>\n\n==Brigade units==\n#'''Brigade Headquarters''' (Calgary)\n#'''[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Medicine Hat]])\n#*A Squadron ([[Medicine Hat]] and [[Lethbridge]])\n#*B Squadron ([[Edmonton]])\n#*Headquarters Squadron ([[Medicine Hat]] and Edmonton)\n#'''[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters (Calgary)\n#*A Squadron (Calgary)\n#*B Squadron (Calgary)\n#*Headquarters Squadron (Calgary)\n#'''20th Field Regiment, RCA'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters (Edmonton)\n#*61st Field Battery (Edmonton)\n#*78th Field Battery ([[Red Deer]])\n#*Headquarters Battery (Edmonton and [[Red Deer]])\n#'''20th Independent Field Battery, RCA''' ([[Lethbridge]])\n#'''[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment]], RCE'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters (Edmonton) \n#*25 Engineer Squadron (Edmonton)\n#*33 Engineer Squadron (Calgary)\n#*Headquarters Squadron (Edmonton and Calgary)\n#'''[[41 Signal Regiment]], RC Sigs'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters (Edmonton)\n#*1 Signal Squadron (Edmonton)\n#*2 Signal Squadron ([[Red Deer]])\n#*3 Signal Squadron (Calgary)\n#*Headquarters Squadron (Edmonton, [[Red Deer]], Calgary)\n#'''[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters (Edmonton)\n#*A Company (Edmonton)\n#*B Company (Edmonton)\n#*C Company ([[Yellowknife]])\n#*Headquarters Company (Edmonton)\n#'''[[The Calgary Highlanders]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters (Calgary)\n#*A Company (Calgary)\n#*B Company (Calgary)\n#*Headquarters Company (Calgary)\n#'''[[41 Service Battalion]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters (Calgary)\n#*14 Service Company (Calgary)\n#*15 Service Company (Edmonton)\n#*Headquarters Company (Calgary and Edmonton)\n#'''[[15 (Edmonton) Field Ambulance]]''' (Edmonton and Calgary)\n#*attached to 41 Canadian Brigade Group under Operational Control from 1 Health Services Group\n\n==History==\nThere are two constants in the organization of the institution that is the [[Canadian Army]], the \"Army Headquarters\" and the \"Units\".  For effective and efficient intermediate command and control, formations such as Corps, Areas, Divisions, Districts, Brigades and Brigade Groups were routinely organized, redesignated, reorganized, or disbanded as required.  41 Canadian Brigade Group is but the latest incarnation of the following fifteen Militia formations that have commanded the Alberta-based [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] units since 1910:\n#'''5th Cavalry Brigade (1910-12)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**15th Light Horse\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|19th Alberta Mounted Rifles]] (redesignated to 19th Alberta Dragoons in 1911)\n#**21st Alberta Hussars, and (left the Brigade in 1911)\n#**23rd Alberta Rangers\n#**25th Battery, C.F.A. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**4th Field Troop, C.E. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**No. 14 Company, C.A.S.C. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**No. 17 Cavalry Field Ambulance (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#'''5th Mounted Brigade (1912-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary (1912-19, 1928-30), Edmonton (1920-27, 1931-34), Pincher Creek (1935-36)\n#*Units under command:\n#**15th Light Horse (redesignated 15th Canadian Light Horse in 1922)\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|South Alberta Horse]] (joined Brigade in 1931 - left the Brigade in 1932)\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|19th Alberta Dragoons]]\n#**23rd Alberta Rangers (left the Brigade in 1922)\n#**25th Battery, C.F.A. (left the Brigade in 1922)\n#**5th Cavalry Brigade Ammunition Column (redesignated 5th Mounted Brigade Ammunition Column \u2013 Between 1919-1922)\n#**4th Field Troop, C.E. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**Wireless Telegraph Detachment, C.E. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**No. 14 Company, C.A.S.C. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**No. 17 Cavalry Field Ambulance (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**The Alberta Mounted Rifles (joined the Brigade in 1922)\n#'''24th Infantry Brigade (1922-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**1st Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29th Infantry Brigade)\n#**2nd Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29th Infantry Brigade)\n#**1st Battalion, The Calgary Regiment (redesignated to [[The Calgary Highlanders]] in 1924)\n#**2nd Battalion, The Calgary Regiment (redesignated to [[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|The Calgary Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**1st Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (redesignated to [[The South Alberta Light Horse|The South Alberta Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**2nd Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29th Infantry Brigade)\n#*Disbanded effective 14 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937#\n#'''29th Infantry Brigade (1923-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#*Units under command:\n#**1st Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (redesignated as [[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|the Edmonton Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**2nd Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (redesignated as the Edmonton Fusiliers in 1924)\n#**2nd Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (redesignated as the North Alberta Regiment in 1924)\n#*Disbanded effective 14 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#'''2ndnd (Reserve) Cavalry Brigade (1936-46)'''\n#*Organized effective 15 December 1936 under General Order 71/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#*Headquartered in Pincher Creek (1936-38) Chauvin, Alberta (1939-42)\n#*Units under command:\n#**15th Alberta Light Horse\n#**19th Alberta Dragoons\n#*Disbanded on 31 March 1946 under General Order 113/46 dated 13 May 1946\n#'''3rd (Reserve) Infantry Brigade (1936-46)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|The South Alberta Regiment]]\n#**The Edmonton Fusiliers\n#**[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|The Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]] \n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|The Calgary Regiment]] (attached)\n#*Reorganized and redesignated to 18th Infantry Brigade effective 1 April 1946 under General Order 116/46 dated 13 May 1946\n#'''41st (Reserve) Brigade Group (1942-46)'''\n#*Formed on 1 April 1942\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton until 1 April 1943 then Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|14th (Reserve) Armoured Regiment, RCAC (Calgary Regiment)]]\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|29th (Reserve) Reconnaissance Regiment]], RCAC (South Alberta Regiment)\n#**41st (Reserve) Field Regiment, R.C.A.\n#**13th (Reserve) Field Company, R.C.E.\n#**E and J sections, No.13 (Reserve) District Signals, R.C.C.S.\n#**4th (Reserve) Armoured Divisional Signals, R.C.C.S.\n#**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, The Edmonton Fusiliers\n#**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, [[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**2nd (Reserve) Battalion, [[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|The Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**No.2 Group, No.10 (Reserve) Divisional Workshop, R.C.O.C.\n#**No.41 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type A), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.42 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.43 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.44 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.8 (Reserve) Field Ambulance, R.C.A.M.C.\n#*Disbanded on 30 January 1946 under General Order 86/1946 dated 2 April 1946\n#'''18th Infantry Brigade (1946-54)'''\n#*Organized effective 15 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#*Reorganized and redesignated from 3rd (Reserve) Infantry Brigade to 18th Infantry Brigade effective 1 April 1946 under General Order 116/46 dated 13 May 1946#\n#'''22 Militia Group (1954-65)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]\n#**18th Field Regiment, RCA\n#**19th Medium Regiment, RCA\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|8th Field Engineer Regiment]], RCE\n#**[[41 Signal Regiment|7th Independent Signals Squadron]], RCCS\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**7th Column, R.C.A.S.C.\n#**21st Medical Company, R.C.A.M.C.\n#**59th Dental Unit, R.C.D.C.\n#**6th Ordnance Company, R.C.O.C.\n#**9th Technical Regiment, R.C.E.M.E.\n#'''23 Militia Group (1954-65)'''\n#*Headquartered in Wainwright\n#'''Alberta Militia District (1965-68)'''\n#'''Northern Alberta Militia District (1968-91)'''\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#'''Southern Alberta Militia District (1968-91)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#'''Alberta District (1991-97)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]\n#**20th Field Regiment, RCA\n#**18th Air Defence Regiment, RCA\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|8th Field Engineer Regiment]], RCE\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|33rd Field Engineer Squadron]], RCE\n#**[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**[[41 Service Battalion|14th (Calgary) Service Battalion]]\n#**[[41 Service Battalion|15th (Edmonton) Service Battalion]]\n#'''41 Canadian Brigade Group (1997-Present)'''\n\n==Past commanders of Alberta's Militia formations==\n*'''5th Cavalry Brigade'''\n**Colonel J. [[Mount James Walker|Walker]] (1910-11)\n**Colonel R. Belcher, [[Order of St Michael and St George|C.M.G.]] (1911-12)\n*'''5th Mounted Brigade'''\n**Colonel R. Belcher, [[Order of St Michael and St George|C.M.G.]] (1912-19)