istrict'''\n**Vacant (1968-70)\n**Colonel L.S. Thompson [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1970-73)\n**Colonel (later Brigadier-General) H.O Wagg, [[Order of Saint John (chartered 1888)|K.St.J.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1973-75)\n**Colonel G.D. Stewart, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1975-77)\n**Colonel R.O. Jacobson, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1977-80)\n**Colonel S.E. Blakely, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1980-83)\n**Colonel P.F. Hughes, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1983-87)\n**Colonel (later Brigadier-General) R.S. Millar, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|O.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1987-90)\n**Colonel J. Fletcher, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1990-91)\n*'''Alberta District'''\n**Colonel J. Fletcher, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1991\u201494)\n**Colonel (later Brigadier-General) R.S. Millar, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|O.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1994-1996)\n**Colonel T. Wolf, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1996-97)\n*'''41 Canadian Brigade Group'''\n**Colonel M. Quinn, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1997-2000)\n**Colonel C. Hamel, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2000-02)\n**Colonel (later Major-General) J.G. Milne, [[Meritorious Service Medal (Canada)|M.S.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2003)\n**Colonel J.D. Gludo, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2003-06)\n**Colonel A. Wreidt, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2006-09)\n**Colonel (later Brigadier-General) T. Putt, [[Meritorious Service Medal (Canada)|M.S.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2009-10)\n**Colonel (later Major-General) P. Bury, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|O.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2010-11)\n**Lieutenant-Colonel M.J. Delaney, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2011)\n**Colonel R.C. Boehli, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2011-13)\n**Colonel J.D. Conrad, [[Meritorious Service Medal (Canada)|M.S.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2013-16)\n**Colonel E. van Weelderen, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2016-19)\n\n==Past sergeants-major of 41 Canadian Brigade Group==\n*Chief Warrant Officer (later Lieutenant-Colonel) R.F. Cruickshank, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1997)\n*Chief Warrant Officer P. Tamblyn, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (1997-2000)\n*Chief Warrant Officer P.J. Wonderham, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2000-03)\n*Chief Warrant Officer R.L. Page, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2003-04)\n*Chief Warrant Officer (later Major) K.J. Griffiths, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2004-07)\n*Chief Warrant Officer (later Captain) A.M.R. Brunelle, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2007-10)\n*Chief Warrant Officer A.M. Thomas, [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2010-12)\n*Chief Warrant Officer E.G. Kelly, [[Meritorious Service Medal (Canada)|M.S.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2012-15)\n*Chief Warrant Officer (later Captain) M.B. Talty, [[Order of Military Merit (Canada)|M.M.M.]], [[Canadian Forces Decoration|C.D.]] (2015-19)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Canadian Forces Land Force Command}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n\n[[Category:Brigades of the Canadian Army]]\n[[Category:Military units and formations established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Organizations based in Calgary]]\n\n{{canada-mil-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox military unit\n|unit_name=41 Canadian Brigade Group\n|native_name={{lang|fr|41<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}\n| image= 41CanadianBrigadeGroup.jpg\n|caption=41&nbsp;CBG badge\n|dates= 1 April 1997 \u2013 present\n|country=[[Canada]]\n|branch=[[Canadian Army]]\n|command_structure=[[3rd Canadian Division]]\n|type=[[Brigade group]]\n|identification_symbol_4=41&nbsp;CBG\n|identification_symbol_4_label=Abbreviation\n|ceremonial_chief=\n|ceremonial_chief_label=Colonel-in-Chief\n|nickname= \"Alberta's Brigade\"\n|march= \"[[Don Quixote (album)|Alberta Bound]]\"\n|motto= Fortune Favours the Bold\n|garrison=LGen Stan Waters Building, [[Calgary]]\n|website={{official URL}}\n<!--Command Team-->\n|commander1=Colonel Michael Vernon, C.D.\n|commander1_label=Commander\n|commander2=Lieutenant-Colonel Chris Hunt, C.D.\n|commander2_label=Deputy Commander\n|commander3=Chief Warrant Officer Scott Doyle, C,D,\n|commander3_label=Brigade Sergeant Major\n|notable_commanders=\n}}\n'''41 Canadian Brigade Group''' (41&nbsp;CBG; {{lang-fr|links=no|41<sup>e</sup> Groupe-brigade du Canada}}) is a [[Canadian Army]] formation of the [[3rd Canadian Division]]. The formation is composed of [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] units within the province of [[Alberta]]. The home station of the brigade is in [[Calgary]].\n\nThe brigade has an establishment of 2,500 all ranks.  The role of the [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] is to be \"a professional part-time force that provides local engagement and a responsive integrated capability, at home or abroad, in sustainment of the Army mission.\"  Most of the soldiers within the brigade serve part time in units or sub-units stationed in their communities.  As the [[Canadian Army]] generates task-specific units for employment on expeditionary and domestic operations under the command of the [[Canadian Joint Operations Command]], 41&nbsp;CBG, as a force generator, is tasked with the following:\n\n# On order provide general-purpose, combat-capable soldiers and specialist sub-subunits (troops or platoons) capable of augmenting the Regular Force on expeditionary operations; and\n# On order provide a domestic response unit (territorial battalion group) or subunits (squadrons or companies) capable of augmenting the Regular Force on domestic operations.\n\n==Corporate Identity==\n<gallery mode=\"packed\">\nFile:41 CBG Camp Flag.png|Brigade Camp Flag\nFile:41 CBG Comd Pennant.jpg|Commander's Pennant\nFile:41 CBG Logo.jpg|Brigade Logo\nFile:41 CBG Brigade Tie.jpg|Brigade Necktie\nFile:41 CBG Brand.jpg|Brigade Brand\n</gallery>\n\n==Brigade Units==\n#'''Brigade Headquarters''' ([[Calgary]])\n#'''[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Medicine Hat]])\n#*A Squadron ([[Medicine Hat]] and [[Lethbridge]])\n#*B Squadron ([[Edmonton]])\n#*Headquarters Squadron ([[Medicine Hat]] and [[Edmonton]])\n#'''[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Calgary]])\n#*A Squadron ([[Calgary]])\n#*B Squadron ([[Calgary]])\n#*Headquarters Squadron ([[Calgary]])\n#'''20<sup>th</sup> Field Regiment, RCA'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Edmonton]])\n#*61<sup>st</sup> Field Battery ([[Edmonton]])\n#*78<sup>th</sup> Field Battery ([[Red Deer]])\n#*Headquarters Battery ([[Edmonton]] and [[Red Deer]])\n#'''20<sup>th</sup> Independent Field Battery, RCA''' ([[Lethbridge]])\n#'''[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment]], RCE'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Edmonton]]) \n#*25 Engineer Squadron ([[Edmonton]])\n#*33 Engineer Squadron ([[Calgary]])\n#*Headquarters Squadron ([[Edmonton]] and [[Calgary]])\n#'''[[41 Signal Regiment]], RC Sigs'''\n#*Regimental Headquarters ([[Edmonton]])\n#*1 Signal Squadron ([[Edmonton]])\n#*2 Signal Squadron ([[Red Deer]])\n#*3 Signal Squadron ([[Calgary]])\n#*Headquarters Squadron ([[Edmonton]], [[Red Deer]], [[Calgary]])\n#'''[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters ([[Edmonton]])\n#*A Company ([[Edmonton]])\n#*B Company ([[Edmonton]])\n#*C Company ([[Yellowknife]])\n#*Headquarters Company ([[Edmonton]])\n#'''[[The Calgary Highlanders]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters ([[Calgary]])\n#*A Company ([[Calgary]])\n#*B Company ([[Calgary]])\n#*Headquarters Company ([[Calgary]])\n#'''[[41 Service Battalion]]'''\n#*Battalion Headquarters ([[Calgary]])\n#*14 Service Company ([[Calgary]])\n#*15 Service Company ([[Edmonton]])\n#*Headquarters Company ([[Calgary]] and [[Edmonton]])\n#'''[[15 (Edmonton) Field Ambulance]]''' ([[Edmonton]] and [[Calgary]])\n#*attached to 41 Canadian Brigade Group under Operational Control from 1 Health Services Group\n\n==History==\nThere are two constants in the organization of the institution that is the [[Canadian Army]], the \"Army Headquarters\" and the \"Units\".  For effective and efficient intermediate command and control, formations such as Corps, Areas, Divisions, Districts, Brigades and Brigade Groups were routinely organized, redesignated, reorganized, or disbanded as required.  41 Canadian Brigade Group is but the latest incarnation of the following fifteen Militia formations that have commanded the Alberta-based [[Primary Reserve#Army_Reserve|Army Reserve]] units since 1910:\n#'''5<sup>th</sup> Cavalry Brigade (1910-12)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**15<sup>th</sup> Light Horse\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|19<sup>th</sup> Alberta Mounted Rifles]] (redesignated to 19<sup>th</sup> Alberta Dragoons in 1911)\n#**21<sup>st</sup> Alberta Hussars, and (left the Brigade in 1911)\n#**23<sup>rd</sup> Alberta Rangers\n#**25<sup>th</sup> Battery, C.F.A. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**4<sup>th</sup> Field Troop, C.E. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**No. 14 Company, C.A.S.C. (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#**No. 17 Cavalry Field Ambulance (joined the Brigade in 1911)\n#'''5<sup>th</sup> Mounted Brigade (1912-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary (1912-19, 1928-30), Edmonton (1920-27, 1931-34), Pincher Creek (1935-36)\n#*Units under command:\n#**15<sup>th</sup> Light Horse (redesignated 15<sup>th</sup> Canadian Light Horse in 1922)\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|South Alberta Horse]] (joined Brigade in 1931 - left the Brigade in 1932)\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|19<sup>th</sup> Alberta Dragoons]]\n#**23<sup>rd</sup> Alberta Rangers (left the Brigade in 1922)\n#**25<sup>th</sup> Battery, C.F.A. (left the Brigade in 1922)\n#**5<sup>th</sup> Cavalry Brigade Ammunition Column (redesignated 5th Mounted Brigade Ammunition Column \u2013 Between 1919-1922)\n#**4<sup>th</sup> Field Troop, C.E. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**Wireless Telegraph Detachment, C.E. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**No. 14 Company, C.A.S.C. (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**No. 17 Cavalry Field Ambulance (left the Brigade 1922)\n#**The Alberta Mounted Rifles (joined the Brigade in 1922)\n#'''24<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade (1922-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**1<sup>st</sup> Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade)\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade)\n#**1<sup>st</sup> Battalion, The Calgary Regiment (redesignated to [[The Calgary Highlanders]] in 1924)\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> Battalion, The Calgary Regiment (redesignated to [[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|The Calgary Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**1<sup>st</sup> Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (redesignated to [[The South Alberta Light Horse|The South Alberta Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (left the Brigade in 1923 to join 29<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade)\n#*Disbanded effective 14 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937#\n#'''29<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade (1923-36)'''\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#*Units under command:\n#**1<sup>st</sup> Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (redesignated as [[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|the Edmonton Regiment]] in 1924)\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> Battalion, The Edmonton Regiment (redesignated as the Edmonton Fusiliers in 1924)\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> Battalion, The Alberta Regiment (redesignated as the North Alberta Regiment in 1924)\n#*Disbanded effective 14 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#'''2nd<sup>nd</sup> (Reserve) Cavalry Brigade (1936-46)'''\n#*Organized effective 15 December 1936 under General Order 71/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#*Headquartered in Pincher Creek (1936-38) Chauvin, Alberta (1939-42)\n#*Units under command:\n#**15<sup>th</sup> Alberta Light Horse\n#**19<sup>th</sup> Alberta Dragoons\n#*Disbanded on 31 March 1946 under General Order 113/46 dated 13 May 1946\n#'''3<sup>rd</sup> (Reserve) Infantry Brigade (1936-46)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|The South Alberta Regiment]]\n#**The Edmonton Fusiliers\n#**[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|The Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]] \n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|The Calgary Regiment]] (attached)\n#*Reorganized and redesignated to 18<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade effective 1 April 1946 under General Order 116/46 dated 13 May 1946\n#'''41<sup>st</sup> (Reserve) Brigade Group (1942-46)'''\n#*Formed on 1 April 1942\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton until 1 April 1943 then Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)|14<sup>th</sup> (Reserve) Armoured Regiment, RCAC (Calgary Regiment)]]\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse|29<sup>th</sup> (Reserve) Reconnaissance Regiment]], RCAC (South Alberta Regiment)\n#**41<sup>st</sup> (Reserve) Field Regiment, R.C.A.\n#**13<sup>th</sup> (Reserve) Field Company, R.C.E.\n#**E and J sections, No.13 (Reserve) District Signals, R.C.C.S.\n#**4<sup>th</sup> (Reserve) Armoured Divisional Signals, R.C.C.S.\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> (Reserve) Battalion, The Edmonton Fusiliers\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> (Reserve) Battalion, [[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**2<sup>nd</sup> (Reserve) Battalion, [[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment|The Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**No.2 Group, No.10 (Reserve) Divisional Workshop, R.C.O.C.\n#**No.41 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type A), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.42 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.43 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.44 (Reserve) Light Aid Detachment (Type B), R.C.O.C.\n#**No.8 (Reserve) Field Ambulance, R.C.A.M.C.\n#*Disbanded on 30 January 1946 under General Order 86/1946 dated 2 April 1946\n#'''18<sup>th</sup> Infantry Brigade (1946-54)'''\n#*Organized effective 15 December 1936 under General Order 73/1937 dated 29 April 1937\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#*Reorganized and redesignated from 3rd (Reserve) Infantry Brigade to 18th Infantry Brigade effective 1 April 1946 under General Order 116/46 dated 13 May 1946#\n#'''22 Militia Group (1954-65)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]\n#**18<sup>th</sup> Field Regiment, RCA\n#**19<sup>th</sup> Medium Regiment, RCA\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|8<sup>th</sup> Field Engineer Regiment]], RCE\n#**[[41 Signal Regiment|7<sup>th</sup> Independent Signals Squadron]], RCCS\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**7<sup>th</sup> Column, R.C.A.S.C.\n#**21<sup>st</sup> Medical Company, R.C.A.M.C.\n#**59<sup>th</sup> Dental Unit, R.C.D.C.\n#**6<sup>th</sup> Ordnance Company, R.C.O.C.\n#**9<sup>th</sup> Technical Regiment, R.C.E.M.E.\n#'''23 Militia Group (1954-65)'''\n#*Headquartered in Wainwright\n#'''Alberta Militia District (1965-68)'''\n#'''Northern Alberta Militia District (1968-91)'''\n#*Headquartered in Edmonton\n#'''Southern Alberta Militia District (1968-91)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#'''Alberta District (1991-97)'''\n#*Headquartered in Calgary\n#*Units under command:\n#**[[The South Alberta Light Horse]]\n#**[[The King's Own Calgary Regiment (RCAC)]]\n#**20<sup>th</sup> Field Regiment, RCA\n#**18<sup>th</sup> Air Defence Regiment, RCA\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|8<sup>th</sup> Field Engineer Regiment]], RCE\n#**[[41 Combat Engineer Regiment|33<sup>rd</sup> Field Engineer Squadron]], RCE\n#**[[The Loyal Edmonton Regiment]]\n#**[[The Calgary Highlanders]]\n#**[[41 Service Battalion|14<sup>th</sup> (Calgary) Service Battalion]]\n#**[[41 Service Battalion|15<sup>th</sup> (Edmonton) Service Batta