{"title_page": "Tule elk", "text_new": "{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = Tule elk\n| image = Tule Elk - Merced National Wildlife Refuge Bill Leikam 12-03-2010.jpg \n| image_caption = Tule bull elk at [[San Luis National Wildlife Refuge Complex|San Luis National Wildlife Refuge]], courtesy of Bill Leikam\n| image2 = Cervus canadensis nannodes at Tomales Point.jpg\n| image2_caption = Tule cow elk at Tomales Point, [[Point Reyes National Seashore]]\n| genus = Cervus\n| species = canadensis\n| species_link = Elk\n| subspecies = nannodes\n| authority = (Merriam, 1905)\n}}\n\n[[File:2007-Tule-elk-rut.jpg|thumb|right |Making rutting call or \"bugle\"]]\n[[File:TuleElkPillsbury1.jpg|thumb |right |Herd at [[Lake Pillsbury]] near Hull Mountain, [[Mendocino National Forest]] in [[Lake County, California]]]]\nThe '''tule elk''' (''Cervus canadensis nannodes'') is a subspecies of [[elk]] found only in [[California]], ranging from the grasslands and marshlands of the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] to the grassy hills on the coast.<ref name=\"Lin\">{{cite web|last =Linse | first =Kim |title =Tule Elk: The Return of A Species | publisher = National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/resourcenewsletter_tuleelk.pdf}}</ref> The subspecies name derives from the [[tule]], a species of [[sedge]] native to freshwater marshes on which the Tule elk feeds. When the Europeans first arrived, an estimated 500,000 tule elk roamed these regions, but by 1870 they were thought to be extirpated.<ref name=NPS/> However, in 1874-1875 a single breeding pair was discovered in the tule marshes of [[Buena Vista Lake]] in the southern [[San Joaquin Valley]].<ref name=McCullough1996>{{cite book |title=From bottleneck to metapopulation: recovery of the tule elk in California, in Metapopulations and wildlife conservation |authors=D.R. McCullough, J. K. Fischer, and J. D. Ballou |editor=D.R. McCullough |year=1996 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/metapopulationsw0000unse/page/375 375\u2013403] |publisher=Island Press |location=Covelo, California |isbn=9781559634588 |url=https://archive.org/details/metapopulationsw0000unse/page/375 }}</ref> Conservation measures were taken to protect the species in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brick  |first =Michael |title =Bow Hunters\u2019 Quest: Stalking an Elk and a Record |publisher = New York Times |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/06/sports/othersports/06elk.html?pagewantd=all |date=2009-01-06 |accessdate=2010-05-26}}</ref> Today, the wild population exceeds 4,000.<ref name=\"Kan\"/> Tule elk can reliably be found in [[Carrizo Plain|Carrizo Plain National Monument]], [[Point Reyes|Point Reyes National Seashore]], portions of the [[Owens Valley]] from [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]] to [[Bishop, California|Bishop]], and on [[Coyote Ridge Open Space Preserve|Coyote Ridge]] in [[Santa Clara Valley]], [[San Jose, California]].\n\n==Description==\nConsidered the smallest of the [[wapiti]] in North America, the tule elk were the dominant large ungulate in California prior to the arrival of the Spanish. It is typically described as the smallest subspecies of all American elks, with the average weight of adult males only {{convert|450|to|550|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and females average of {{convert|375|to|425|lb|kg|abbr=on}}. Although tule elk have been reported as half the size of the [[Roosevelt elk]], and sometimes referred to as the dwarf elk, this moniker may be misleading as the smaller size of some tule elk may reflect poor nutrition of elk subsisting on marginal habitat such as the [[Owens River]] watershed. [[California Department of Fish and Wildlife]] records show recent bull elk on Grizzly Island in Suisun Bay weigh up to {{convert|900|lb|kg}}.<ref name=Cunningham/> This is a similar size to Roosevelt elk bulls which weigh between {{convert|700|lb|kg}} and {{convert|1100|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite book |last = Robb |first = Bob |title = The Ultimate Guide to Elk Hunting |date=January 2001 |publisher = The Lyons Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-180-9 }}</ref> Wildlife biologist Dale McCullough described an elk transplanted from [[Buttonwillow, California|Buttonwillow]] in the [[San Joaquin Valley]] to a golf course in [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] that grew to the size of a [[Rocky Mountain elk]].<ref name=McCullough1969>{{cite book |title=The Tule Elk, Its History, Behavior, and Ecology, University of California Publications in Zoology |author=Dale R. McCullough |year=1969 |publisher=University of California Press |volume=88 |pages=209 |isbn=9780520019218 }}</ref> Also hunter H. C. Banta described the tule elk in the 1850s as \"I found no difference in size between these elk and the Oregon, Washington, Wyoming and Colorado elk, and felt sure that the bulls would weight 700 to 800 pounds\".<ref name=Cunningham>{{cite book |title=A State of Change: Forgotten Landscapes of California |author=Laura Cunningham |year=2010 |publisher=Heyday |pages=350 |isbn=9781597141369 }}</ref>\n\nThe calves are similar to deer fawns, with brown coats and white spots.\n\nGenetic studies based on [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] and [[nuclear DNA]] confirm that Tule elk, Roosevelt elk and Rocky Mountain elk should be considered distinct subspecies.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Microsatellite Analysis of Three Subspecies of Elk (Cervus elaphus) in California |authors=E. P. Meredith, J. A. Rodzen, J. D. Banks, R. Schaefer, H. B. Ernest, T. R. Famula, and B. P. May |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=88 |number=3 |pages=801\u2013808 |year=2007 |url=http://genome-lab.ucdavis.edu/publications/2007%20Meredith-elk.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 |doi=10.1644/06-mamm-a-014r.1}}</ref> The 2010 nuclear DNA study found five alleles at one locus, indicating that there has either been a mutation at this locus subsequent to the single breeding pair reported by Henry Miller and nineteenth century game warden A. C. Tibbet, or there were three surviving tule elk at the genetic bottleneck.\n\n==History==\nThe first European explorer to see tule elk was likely [[Sir Francis Drake]] who landed in July 1579 probably in today's [[Drake's Bay]], [[Marin County, California]]: \"The inland we found to be far different from the shoare, a goodly country and fruitful soil, stored with many blessings fit for the use of man: infinite was the company of very large and fat deer, which there we saw by thousands as we supposed in a herd...\"<ref name=McCullough1969/>{ A more definitive second encounter 16 years later was described by [[Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o]], who was shipwrecked in December 1595, and in Drake's Bay with certainty. Cerme\u00f1o's account described \"deer walking about, the largest ever found, as could be seen by the antlers, of which the Captain carried away a sample\". On a trip inland they found \"a great quantity of deer horns, one of which, measured before this witness, showed sixteen palmas [11 feet] from point to point.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Voyage to California of Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o in 1595 |authors=Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o and Henry R. Wagner |year=1924  |journal=California Historical Society Quarterly |volume=3 |number=1 |pages=3-24 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/25613599?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=April 11, 2020 }}</ref> Cermeno and his crew made a small boat from their wrecked [[Manila galleon]] and sailed back to [[Acapulco, Mexico]] with but a single trophy of their voyage to the [[Philippines]], the set of large elk antlers.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Description of Distant Roads |authors=Juan Cresp\u00ed and Alan K. Brown |publisher=San Diego State University Press |year=2001 |location=San Diego, California |page=15 |isbn=978-1879691643 }}</ref> Next, [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]] described seeing elk on his December 1602 exploration of the [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] area, \"Among the animals there are large, fierce bears, and other animals called elks, from which they make elk leather jackets.\" <ref name=Evermann>{{cite journal |title=An Attempt to Save California Elk |author=Barton Warren Evermann |journal=California Fish and Game |date=April 1915 |volume=1 |number=3 |pages=85\u201396 }}</ref> The arrival of the Spanish in the late 18th century introduced cattle and horses to the grasslands of the Central Valley, competing with the native elk. Unrestricted hunting further reduced the herds. By the time elk hunting was banned by the State Legislature in 1873, the tule elk was believed to be extinct.<ref name=StateReserve>{{cite report |title=Tule Elk State Natural Reserve Brochure |publisher=California State Parks |url=http://www.parks.ca.gov/pages/584/files/TuleElkSNRWebBrochure2012Rev.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 }}</ref>\n\nCalifornia cattle baron [[Henry Miller (rancher)|Henry Miller]] protected tule elk after a pair was discovered on his ranch in the tule marshes near [[Buena Vista Lake]] by game warden A. C. Tibbett in 1874. Miller ordered his men to protect the elk and is credited for the survival of the subspecies.<ref name=StateReserve/> After his death, the huge Miller-Lux ranch was subdivided and the hunting of the elk resumed. The population was reduced to 72 head. By 1895, [[habitat loss]] and [[poaching]] had reduced the elk population to only 28.<ref name=\"Kan\">{{cite web|last =Kanewske |first =Rachel |title =The Biogeography of the Tule Elk |publisher = San Francisco State University |url = http://online.sfsu.edu/bholzman/courses/Fall00Projects/Tule_elk.html}}</ref> In the years that followed, the elk were transplanted 21 times, with each attempt failing.\n\nIn 1933, rancher Walter Dow took a small group of penned elk to his ranch in [[Owens Valley]], east of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]. Although not native habitat for the elk, they thrived. In the same year, the state put a small herd at [[Cache Creek (Sacramento River)|Cache Creek]]. This herd has not fared well due to poor range conditions. This herd may have interbred with the Rocky Mountain elk which were introduced near [[Mount Shasta]].\n\nIn 1960, the state held a hearing in Owens Valley to determine how many elk should be allowed to live there. They decided the elk should be hunted to limit their numbers to under 500 animals. Through efforts of the California Department of Fish and Game, three permanent elk herds were established in California. By 1969, the Tupman State Reserve (32), Cache Creek (80) and Owens Valley, Inyo County (300 elk) were in place.\n\nA private citizen from Los Angeles, Beula Edmiston, formed a group to attempt a preservation program for the elk. After more than 10 years of lobbying both on the federal and state levels, in 1971, California passed legislation (the Behr bill) requiring the elk may not be hunted until their numbers surpass 2,000 head statewide or until it could be determined that suitable elk habitat no longer existed in the state, and mandated the California Department of Resources to reintroduce the elk into former habitats wherever possible.\n\nIn 1976, the US Congress passed a resolution which stated 2000 tule elk is an appropriate national goal, and directed federal agencies to make federal lands available for preservation of tule elk.<ref>The Tule Elk in California, Bureau of Land Management, PL 94 389 March 1980</ref> An Interagency Task Force<ref>A Management Plan for the Conservation of Tule Elk, The Tule Elk Interagency Task Force, June 1979</ref> of representatives from the National Park Service, US Forest Service, the Armed Forces, Bureau of Land Management, California Department of Parks and Recreation, and the California Department of Fish and Game<ref>Tule elk in California-report to the legislature, May 1978, Resources Agency, Dept. of Fish and Game</ref> selected sites for the reintroduction of tule elk within the state. A herd was established at the San Luis Wildlife Refuge in 1974, and elk were released at the Concord Naval Weapons Station in 1977. In 1978, herds were established at [[Mount Hamilton (California)|Mount Hamilton]] in [[Santa Clara County]], [[Lake Pillsbury]] in [[Lake County, California|Lake County]], Jawbone Canyon in [[Kern County]], [[Point Reyes National Seashore]], [[Fort Hunter Liggett]] Military Reservation, and [[Camp Roberts, California|Camp Roberts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/environment/article233662527.html|title=Feds plan to kill elk at Point Reyes to protect ranches. Here\u2019s how you can weigh in|last=Sabalow|first=Ryan|date=August 8, 2019|work=Sacramento Bee|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Historic Range and Current population==\n[[File:Dominant tule elk bull, Point Reyes National Seashore.jpg|thumb|upright|A Tule bull at Point Reyes National Seashore in 2018]]\nMcCullough identified nineteenth century tule elk antler specimens collected in three separate locations north of the [[San Francisco Bay]]: [[Sonoma, California|Sonoma]] in [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma County]], as well as [[San Geronimo, California|San Geronimo]]  and  [[Tomales, California|Tomales]] both in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]].<ref name=McCullough1969/>\n\nBy 1986 numbers had increased to over 2,000 individuals distributed among 22 populations throughout California, largely due to successful reintroduction programs.<ref name=McCullough1996/> By 1998, California's tule elk population exceeded 3,200.<ref name=NPS>{{cite report |title=Tule Elk - The Return of a Species |publisher=National Park Service |year=1998 |url=http://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/resourcenewsletter_tuleelk.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 }}</ref><ref>Livezey KB. 1993. Tule elk relocated to Brushy Mountain, Mendocino County, California. California Fish and Game 79:131\u2013132.</ref> In 2007, the statewide population was estimated at 3,800.<ref>{{cite report |title=Safe Passage for the Coyote Valley - A Wildlife Linkage for the Highway 101 Corridor |author1=Julie Phillips |author2=Ryan Phillips |author3=Neela Srinivasan |author4=Deborah Aso |author5=Wendy Lao |author6=Pat Cornely  |last-author-amp=yes |publisher=De Anza College |year=2012 |url=http://www.deanza.edu/es/wildlifecorrproj/Safe%20Passagelowres.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-27 }}</ref> A 2014 report placed the statewide population at 4,200 in 22 herds.<ref name=BayNature>{{cite magazine |title=Tule Elk Relocated as Numbers Rebound |author=Elizabeth Devitt |magazine=Bay Nature |date=May 7, 2014 |url=https://baynature.org/articles/tule-elk-relocated-numbers-rebound/ |accessdate=2016-02-27 }}</ref>\n\nSmall numbers of tule elk in Point Reyes have tested positive for [[Mycobacterium avium subspecies paratuberculosis]] or \"MAP\", a wasting disease known as [[Johne's Disease]]. The bacteria was apparently transmitted by dairy cattle or spraying of cattle manure on pasturelands. In 2016 more tule elk tested positive after being euthanized so that their gut tissue could be analyzed. Cattle transmitted the disease to the Tomales Point elk herd shortly after they were first established there in 1978.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Point Reyes Elk Test Positive for Disease. Are Cattle to Blame? |author=Alison Hawkes |journal=Bay Nature |date=February 28, 2016 |url=https://baynature.org/article/point-reyes-elk-test-positive-for-disease/ |accessdate=December 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Diet and impact on native grasslands==\n[[File:Tupeelkpointreyes.jpg|thumb |right |Tule elk at [[Point Reyes]]]]\nTwo male and eight female elk were translocated from [[Merced County, California]] to [[Tomales Point]] on [[Point Reyes National Seashore]] in March 1978. The elk showed signs of nutritional stress including [[copper deficiency]] and antler anomalies by summer 1979 and two elk died. One explanation was [[molybdenum]] which expresses as copper deficiency.  A former [[Molybdenum mining in the United States|molybdenum mine]] existed in that area of the Point Reyes National Seashore.  Other possible explanations include failure to remove cattle until 1979 and the fact that 1977 and 1978 were drought years. Birth rates remained negligible until 1981, when they began reproducing at predicted maximum rates. Studies of fecal material documented that the tule elk preferred grasses and [[forb]]s with little use of shrubs such as willow.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Elk and Deer Diets in a Coastal Prairie-Scrub Mosaic, California |authors=Peter J. P. Gogan and Reginald H. Barrett |journal=Journal of Range Management |volume=48 |number=4 |date=July 1995 |pages=327\u2013335 |jstor=4002485 |doi=10.2307/4002485 }}</ref> These results are consistent with findings on the [[Diablo Range]], [[Santa Clara County]] elk herd where more than 50% of the tule elk diet were grasses.<ref>{{cite thesis |title=Acclimation of reintroduced tule elk in the Diablo Range, California, M.S. Thesis |author=Julie A. Phillips |year=1985 |publisher=San Jose State University |location=San Jose, California |pages=106 }}</ref>\n\nA 2007 study at the Tomales Point Elk Reserve showed that tule elk appear to play a critical role in preventing succession of open grasslands to less diverse, shrub-dominated ecosystems. Elk grazing had a positive impact on native grassland species abundance and diversity, and seemed to increase the richness and abundance of some exotic taxa while reducing [[Holcus lanatus]] \u2014 a highly invasive exotic grass which is a major problem in [[Mesic habitat|mesic perennial grasslands]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Influence of a Large Herbivore Reintroduction on Plant Invasions and Community Composition in a California Grassland |authors=Brent E. Johnson, J. Hall Cushman |journal=Conservation Biology |year=2007 |volume=21 |number=2 |pages=515\u2013526 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2006.00610.x|pmid=17391201 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe Environmental Science Department at [[De Anza College]], in [[Cupertino, California]] offers a twice-yearly course that focuses on field observation of the tule elk found in [[Santa Clara County, California]]. This class provides an overview on the history of tule elk reintroduction, habitat use, home range characteristics, behaviors and other natural history insights. It also discusses the underlying social, economic and political issues associated with the near extinction and restoration of this subspecies of North American elk. It involves off-campus field trips to visit existing tule elk herds.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Elk]]\n*[[Red deer]]\n*[[Rocky Mountain elk]]\n*[[Roosevelt elk]]\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* The Return of the Tule Elk-Verna R. Johnston-Pacific Discovery, Vol. 31, Number 1, pages 14\u201325, Jan-Feb, 1978 California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco\n* The Tule Elk Preservation Act of 1976-Public Law 94-389\n* Tule Elk Management Plan and Environmental Assessment, Oct. 1997\n* History of the California Tule Elk, Gerhard Bakker, Los Angeles City College, 1961\n* Tule Elk in California, History, Current Status, and Management Recommendations, Gene Scott Fowler, UC Berkeley, July 1985\n* Acclimation of Reintroduced Tule Elk in the Diablo Range, California,  Julie A.Phillips,  Thesis, San Jose State University, May 1985\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://science.kqed.org/quest/video/elk-return-to-the-bay-area/ Video on Pt. Reyes and Mt. Hamilton Elk: Elk Return to the Bay Area by KQED: QUEST Northern California ]\n*[http://www.sfgate.com/getoutside/1996/aug/elkinfo.html Tule Elk at Point Reyes National Seashore]\n*[http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=584 Tule Elk State Natural Reserve]\n*[http://www.dfg.ca.gov/regions/6/Conservation/TuleElkHistory.html Tule Elk History in the Owens Valley]\n*[https://vimeo.com/220899416 North Coyote Ridge (Santa Clara County) Elk Herd filmed by Michael Hundt 2017]\n*[http://www.deanza.edu/publications/catalog/search/schdetail.html?detailNum=ESCI9010-11 ESCI 90: Santa Clara County Field Studies: Tule Elk]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q755724}}\n\n[[Category:Elk and red deer]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of California]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "text_old": "{{Subspeciesbox\n| name = Tule elk\n| image = Tule Elk - Merced National Wildlife Refuge Bill Leikam 12-03-2010.jpg \n| image_caption = Tule bull elk at [[San Luis National Wildlife Refuge Complex|San Luis National Wildlife Refuge]], courtesy of Bill Leikam\n| image2 = Cervus canadensis nannodes at Tomales Point.jpg\n| image2_caption = Tule cow elk at Tomales Point, [[Point Reyes National Seashore]]\n| genus = Cervus\n| species = canadensis\n| species_link = Elk\n| subspecies = nannodes\n| authority = (Merriam, 1905)\n}}\n\n[[File:2007-Tule-elk-rut.jpg|thumb|right |Making rutting call or \"bugle\"]]\n[[File:TuleElkPillsbury1.jpg|thumb |right |Herd at [[Lake Pillsbury]] near Hull Mountain, [[Mendocino National Forest]] in [[Lake County, California]]]]\nThe '''tule elk''' (''Cervus canadensis nannodes'') is a subspecies of [[elk]] found only in [[California]], ranging from the grasslands and marshlands of the [[Central Valley (California)|Central Valley]] to the grassy hills on the coast.<ref name=\"Lin\">{{cite web|last =Linse | first =Kim |title =Tule Elk: The Return of A Species | publisher = National Park Service| url = http://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/resourcenewsletter_tuleelk.pdf}}</ref> The subspecies name derives from the [[tule]], a species of [[sedge]] native to freshwater marshes on which the Tule elk feeds. When the Europeans first arrived, an estimated 500,000 tule elk roamed these regions, but by 1870 they were thought to be extirpated.<ref name=NPS/> However, in 1874-1875 a single breeding pair was discovered in the tule marshes of [[Buena Vista Lake]] in the southern [[San Joaquin Valley]].<ref name=McCullough1996>{{cite book |title=From bottleneck to metapopulation: recovery of the tule elk in California, in Metapopulations and wildlife conservation |authors=D.R. McCullough, J. K. Fischer, and J. D. Ballou |editor=D.R. McCullough |year=1996 |pages=[https://archive.org/details/metapopulationsw0000unse/page/375 375\u2013403] |publisher=Island Press |location=Covelo, California |isbn=9781559634588 |url=https://archive.org/details/metapopulationsw0000unse/page/375 }}</ref> Conservation measures were taken to protect the species in the 1970s.<ref>{{cite news |last=Brick  |first =Michael |title =Bow Hunters\u2019 Quest: Stalking an Elk and a Record |publisher = New York Times |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/01/06/sports/othersports/06elk.html?pagewantd=all |date=2009-01-06 |accessdate=2010-05-26}}</ref> Today, the wild population exceeds 4,000.<ref name=\"Kan\"/> Tule elk can reliably be found in [[Carrizo Plain|Carrizo Plain National Monument]], [[Point Reyes|Point Reyes National Seashore]], portions of the [[Owens Valley]] from [[Lone Pine, California|Lone Pine]] to [[Bishop, California|Bishop]], and on [[Coyote Ridge Open Space Preserve|Coyote Ridge]] in [[Santa Clara Valley]], [[San Jose, California]].\n\n==Description==\nConsidered the smallest of the [[wapiti]] in North America, the tule elk were the dominant large ungulate in California prior to the arrival of the Spanish. It is typically described as the smallest subspecies of all American elks, with the average weight of adult males only {{convert|450|to|550|lb|kg|abbr=on}} and females average of {{convert|375|to|425|lb|kg|abbr=on}}. Although tule elk have been reported as half the size of the [[Roosevelt elk]], and sometimes referred to as the dwarf elk, this moniker may be misleading as the smaller size of some tule elk may reflect poor nutrition of elk subsisting on marginal habitat such as the [[Owens River]] watershed. [[California Department of Fish and Wildlife]] records show recent bull elk on Grizzly Island in Suisun Bay weigh up to {{convert|900|lb|kg}}.<ref name=Cunningham/> This is a similar size to Roosevelt elk bulls which weigh between {{convert|700|lb|kg}} and {{convert|1100|lb|kg}}.<ref>{{cite book |last = Robb |first = Bob |title = The Ultimate Guide to Elk Hunting |date=January 2001 |publisher = The Lyons Press |isbn = 978-1-58574-180-9 }}</ref> Wildlife biologist Dale McCullough described an elk transplanted from [[Buttonwillow, California|Buttonwillow]] in the [[San Joaquin Valley]] to a golf course in [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] that grew to the size of a [[Rocky Mountain elk]].<ref name=McCullough1969>{{cite book |title=The Tule Elk, Its History, Behavior, and Ecology, University of California Publications in Zoology |author=Dale R. McCullough |year=1969 |publisher=University of California Press |volume=88 |pages=209 |isbn=9780520019218 }}</ref> Also hunter H. C. Banta described the tule elk in the 1850s as \"I found no difference in size between these elk and the Oregon, Washington, Wyoming and Colorado elk, and felt sure that the bulls would weight 700 to 800 pounds\".<ref name=Cunningham>{{cite book |title=A State of Change: Forgotten Landscapes of California |author=Laura Cunningham |year=2010 |publisher=Heyday |pages=350 |isbn=9781597141369 }}</ref>\n\nThe calves are similar to deer fawns, with brown coats and white spots.\n\nGenetic studies based on [[Mitochondrial DNA|mitochondrial]] and [[nuclear DNA]] confirm that Tule elk, Roosevelt elk and Rocky Mountain elk should be considered distinct subspecies.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Microsatellite Analysis of Three Subspecies of Elk (Cervus elaphus) in California |authors=E. P. Meredith, J. A. Rodzen, J. D. Banks, R. Schaefer, H. B. Ernest, T. R. Famula, and B. P. May |journal=Journal of Mammalogy |volume=88 |number=3 |pages=801\u2013808 |year=2007 |url=http://genome-lab.ucdavis.edu/publications/2007%20Meredith-elk.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 |doi=10.1644/06-mamm-a-014r.1}}</ref> The 2010 nuclear DNA study found five alleles at one locus, indicating that there has either been a mutation at this locus subsequent to the single breeding pair reported by Henry Miller and nineteenth century game warden A. C. Tibbet, or there were three surviving tule elk at the genetic bottleneck.\n\n==History==\nThe first European explorer to see tule elk was likely [[Sir Francis Drake]] who landed in July 1579 probably in today's [[Drake's Bay]], [[Marin County, California]]: \"The inland we found to be far different from the shoare, a goodly country and fruitful soil, stored with many blessings fit for the use of man: infinite was the company of very large and fat deer, which there we saw by thousands as we supposed in a herd...\"<ref name=McCullough1969/>{ A more definitive second encounter 16 years later was described by [[Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o]], who was shipwrecked in December 1595, and in Drake's Bay with certainty. Cerme\u00f1o's account described \"deer walking about, the largest ever found, as could be seen by the antlers, of which the Captain carried away a sample\". On a trip inland they found \"a great quantity of deer horns, one of which, measured before this witness, showed sixteen palmas [11 feet] from point to point.\"<ref>{{cite journal |title=The Voyage to California of Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o in 1595 |authors=Sebastian Rodriguez Cerme\u00f1o and Henry R. Wagner |year=1924  |journal=California Historical Society Quarterly |volume=3 |number=1 |pages=3-24 |url=https://www.jstor.org/stable/25613599?seq=1#metadata_info_tab_contents |accessdate=April 11, 2020 }}</ref> Cermeno and his crew made a small boat from their wrecked [[Manila galleon]] and sailed back to [[Acapulco, Mexico]] with but a single trophy of their voyage to the [[Phillippines]], the set of large elk antlers.<ref>{{cite book |title=A Description of Distant Roads |authors=Juan Cresp\u00ed and Alan K. Brown |publisher=San Diego State University Press |year=2001 |location=San Diego, California |page=15 |isbn=978-1879691643 }}</ref> Next, [[Sebasti\u00e1n Vizca\u00edno]] described seeing elk on his December 1602 exploration of the [[Monterey, California|Monterey]] area, \"Among the animals there are large, fierce bears, and other animals called elks, from which they make elk leather jackets.\" <ref name=Evermann>{{cite journal |title=An Attempt to Save California Elk |author=Barton Warren Evermann |journal=California Fish and Game |date=April 1915 |volume=1 |number=3 |pages=85\u201396 }}</ref> The arrival of the Spanish in the late 18th century introduced cattle and horses to the grasslands of the Central Valley, competing with the native elk. Unrestricted hunting further reduced the herds. By the time elk hunting was banned by the State Legislature in 1873, the tule elk was believed to be extinct.<ref name=StateReserve>{{cite report |title=Tule Elk State Natural Reserve Brochure |publisher=California State Parks |url=http://www.parks.ca.gov/pages/584/files/TuleElkSNRWebBrochure2012Rev.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 }}</ref>\n\nCalifornia cattle baron [[Henry Miller (rancher)|Henry Miller]] protected tule elk after a pair was discovered on his ranch in the tule marshes near [[Buena Vista Lake]] by game warden A. C. Tibbett in 1874. Miller ordered his men to protect the elk and is credited for the survival of the subspecies.<ref name=StateReserve/> After his death, the huge Miller-Lux ranch was subdivided and the hunting of the elk resumed. The population was reduced to 72 head. By 1895, [[habitat loss]] and [[poaching]] had reduced the elk population to only 28.<ref name=\"Kan\">{{cite web|last =Kanewske |first =Rachel |title =The Biogeography of the Tule Elk |publisher = San Francisco State University |url = http://online.sfsu.edu/bholzman/courses/Fall00Projects/Tule_elk.html}}</ref> In the years that followed, the elk were transplanted 21 times, with each attempt failing.\n\nIn 1933, rancher Walter Dow took a small group of penned elk to his ranch in [[Owens Valley]], east of the [[Sierra Nevada (U.S.)|Sierra Nevada]]. Although not native habitat for the elk, they thrived. In the same year, the state put a small herd at [[Cache Creek (Sacramento River)|Cache Creek]]. This herd has not fared well due to poor range conditions. This herd may have interbred with the Rocky Mountain elk which were introduced near [[Mount Shasta]].\n\nIn 1960, the state held a hearing in Owens Valley to determine how many elk should be allowed to live there. They decided the elk should be hunted to limit their numbers to under 500 animals. Through efforts of the California Department of Fish and Game, three permanent elk herds were established in California. By 1969, the Tupman State Reserve (32), Cache Creek (80) and Owens Valley, Inyo County (300 elk) were in place.\n\nA private citizen from Los Angeles, Beula Edmiston, formed a group to attempt a preservation program for the elk. After more than 10 years of lobbying both on the federal and state levels, in 1971, California passed legislation (the Behr bill) requiring the elk may not be hunted until their numbers surpass 2,000 head statewide or until it could be determined that suitable elk habitat no longer existed in the state, and mandated the California Department of Resources to reintroduce the elk into former habitats wherever possible.\n\nIn 1976, the US Congress passed a resolution which stated 2000 tule elk is an appropriate national goal, and directed federal agencies to make federal lands available for preservation of tule elk.<ref>The Tule Elk in California, Bureau of Land Management, PL 94 389 March 1980</ref> An Interagency Task Force<ref>A Management Plan for the Conservation of Tule Elk, The Tule Elk Interagency Task Force, June 1979</ref> of representatives from the National Park Service, US Forest Service, the Armed Forces, Bureau of Land Management, California Department of Parks and Recreation, and the California Department of Fish and Game<ref>Tule elk in California-report to the legislature, May 1978, Resources Agency, Dept. of Fish and Game</ref> selected sites for the reintroduction of tule elk within the state. A herd was established at the San Luis Wildlife Refuge in 1974, and elk were released at the Concord Naval Weapons Station in 1977. In 1978, herds were established at [[Mount Hamilton (California)|Mount Hamilton]] in [[Santa Clara County]], [[Lake Pillsbury]] in [[Lake County, California|Lake County]], Jawbone Canyon in [[Kern County]], [[Point Reyes National Seashore]], [[Fort Hunter Liggett]] Military Reservation, and [[Camp Roberts, California|Camp Roberts]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sacbee.com/news/local/environment/article233662527.html|title=Feds plan to kill elk at Point Reyes to protect ranches. Here\u2019s how you can weigh in|last=Sabalow|first=Ryan|date=August 8, 2019|work=Sacramento Bee|access-date=August 9, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Historic Range and Current population==\n[[File:Dominant tule elk bull, Point Reyes National Seashore.jpg|thumb|upright|A Tule bull at Point Reyes National Seashore in 2018]]\nMcCullough identified nineteenth century tule elk antler specimens collected in three separate locations north of the [[San Francisco Bay]]: [[Sonoma, California|Sonoma]] in [[Sonoma County, California|Sonoma County]], as well as [[San Geronimo, California|San Geronimo]]  and  [[Tomales, California|Tomales]] both in [[Marin County, California|Marin County]].<ref name=McCullough1969/>\n\nBy 1986 numbers had increased to over 2,000 individuals distributed among 22 populations throughout California, largely due to successful reintroduction programs.<ref name=McCullough1996/> By 1998, California's tule elk population exceeded 3,200.<ref name=NPS>{{cite report |title=Tule Elk - The Return of a Species |publisher=National Park Service |year=1998 |url=http://www.nps.gov/pore/planyourvisit/upload/resourcenewsletter_tuleelk.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-20 }}</ref><ref>Livezey KB. 1993. Tule elk relocated to Brushy Mountain, Mendocino County, California. California Fish and Game 79:131\u2013132.</ref> In 2007, the statewide population was estimated at 3,800.<ref>{{cite report |title=Safe Passage for the Coyote Valley - A Wildlife Linkage for the Highway 101 Corridor |author1=Julie Phillips |author2=Ryan Phillips |author3=Neela Srinivasan |author4=Deborah Aso |author5=Wendy Lao |author6=Pat Cornely  |last-author-amp=yes |publisher=De Anza College |year=2012 |url=http://www.deanza.edu/es/wildlifecorrproj/Safe%20Passagelowres.pdf |accessdate=2013-01-27 }}</ref> A 2014 report placed the statewide population at 4,200 in 22 herds.<ref name=BayNature>{{cite magazine |title=Tule Elk Relocated as Numbers Rebound |author=Elizabeth Devitt |magazine=Bay Nature |date=May 7, 2014 |url=https://baynature.org/articles/tule-elk-relocated-numbers-rebound/ |accessdate=2016-02-27 }}</ref>\n\nSmall numbers of tule elk in Point Reyes have tested positive for [[Mycobacterium avium subspecies paratuberculosis]] or \"MAP\", a wasting disease known as [[Johne's Disease]]. The bacteria was apparently transmitted by dairy cattle or spraying of cattle manure on pasturelands. In 2016 more tule elk tested positive after being euthanized so that their gut tissue could be analyzed. Cattle transmitted the disease to the Tomales Point elk herd shortly after they were first established there in 1978.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Point Reyes Elk Test Positive for Disease. Are Cattle to Blame? |author=Alison Hawkes |journal=Bay Nature |date=February 28, 2016 |url=https://baynature.org/article/point-reyes-elk-test-positive-for-disease/ |accessdate=December 3, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n==Diet and impact on native grasslands==\n[[File:Tupeelkpointreyes.jpg|thumb |right |Tule elk at [[Point Reyes]]]]\nTwo male and eight female elk were translocated from [[Merced County, California]] to [[Tomales Point]] on [[Point Reyes National Seashore]] in March 1978. The elk showed signs of nutritional stress including [[copper deficiency]] and antler anomalies by summer 1979 and two elk died. One explanation was [[molybdenum]] which expresses as copper deficiency.  A former [[Molybdenum mining in the United States|molybdenum mine]] existed in that area of the Point Reyes National Seashore.  Other possible explanations include failure to remove cattle until 1979 and the fact that 1977 and 1978 were drought years. Birth rates remained negligible until 1981, when they began reproducing at predicted maximum rates. Studies of fecal material documented that the tule elk preferred grasses and [[forb]]s with little use of shrubs such as willow.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Elk and Deer Diets in a Coastal Prairie-Scrub Mosaic, California |authors=Peter J. P. Gogan and Reginald H. Barrett |journal=Journal of Range Management |volume=48 |number=4 |date=July 1995 |pages=327\u2013335 |jstor=4002485 |doi=10.2307/4002485 }}</ref> These results are consistent with findings on the [[Diablo Range]], [[Santa Clara County]] elk herd where more than 50% of the tule elk diet were grasses.<ref>{{cite thesis |title=Acclimation of reintroduced tule elk in the Diablo Range, California, M.S. Thesis |author=Julie A. Phillips |year=1985 |publisher=San Jose State University |location=San Jose, California |pages=106 }}</ref>\n\nA 2007 study at the Tomales Point Elk Reserve showed that tule elk appear to play a critical role in preventing succession of open grasslands to less diverse, shrub-dominated ecosystems. Elk grazing had a positive impact on native grassland species abundance and diversity, and seemed to increase the richness and abundance of some exotic taxa while reducing [[Holcus lanatus]] \u2014 a highly invasive exotic grass which is a major problem in [[Mesic habitat|mesic perennial grasslands]].<ref>{{cite journal |title=Influence of a Large Herbivore Reintroduction on Plant Invasions and Community Composition in a California Grassland |authors=Brent E. Johnson, J. Hall Cushman |journal=Conservation Biology |year=2007 |volume=21 |number=2 |pages=515\u2013526 |doi=10.1111/j.1523-1739.2006.00610.x|pmid=17391201 }}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nThe Environmental Science Department at [[De Anza College]], in [[Cupertino, California]] offers a twice-yearly course that focuses on field observation of the tule elk found in [[Santa Clara County, California]]. This class provides an overview on the history of tule elk reintroduction, habitat use, home range characteristics, behaviors and other natural history insights. It also discusses the underlying social, economic and political issues associated with the near extinction and restoration of this subspecies of North American elk. It involves off-campus field trips to visit existing tule elk herds.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Elk]]\n*[[Red deer]]\n*[[Rocky Mountain elk]]\n*[[Roosevelt elk]]\n\n== References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n* The Return of the Tule Elk-Verna R. Johnston-Pacific Discovery, Vol. 31, Number 1, pages 14\u201325, Jan-Feb, 1978 California Academy of Sciences, San Francisco\n* The Tule Elk Preservation Act of 1976-Public Law 94-389\n* Tule Elk Management Plan and Environmental Assessment, Oct. 1997\n* History of the California Tule Elk, Gerhard Bakker, Los Angeles City College, 1961\n* Tule Elk in California, History, Current Status, and Management Recommendations, Gene Scott Fowler, UC Berkeley, July 1985\n* Acclimation of Reintroduced Tule Elk in the Diablo Range, California,  Julie A.Phillips,  Thesis, San Jose State University, May 1985\n\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://science.kqed.org/quest/video/elk-return-to-the-bay-area/ Video on Pt. Reyes and Mt. Hamilton Elk: Elk Return to the Bay Area by KQED: QUEST Northern California ]\n*[http://www.sfgate.com/getoutside/1996/aug/elkinfo.html Tule Elk at Point Reyes National Seashore]\n*[http://www.parks.ca.gov/?page_id=584 Tule Elk State Natural Reserve]\n*[http://www.dfg.ca.gov/regions/6/Conservation/TuleElkHistory.html Tule Elk History in the Owens Valley]\n*[https://vimeo.com/220899416 North Coyote Ridge (Santa Clara County) Elk Herd filmed by Michael Hundt 2017]\n*[http://www.deanza.edu/publications/catalog/search/schdetail.html?detailNum=ESCI9010-11 ESCI 90: Santa Clara County Field Studies: Tule Elk]\n\n{{Taxonbar|from=Q755724}}\n\n[[Category:Elk and red deer]]\n[[Category:Endemic fauna of California]]\n[[Category:Fauna of the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n", "name_user": "EdmundT", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:Spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tule_elk"}
{"title_page": "Iain McNicol", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Lord McNicol of West Kilbride\n|image       = Official portrait of Lord McNicol of West Kilbride crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = McNicol in 2019\n|office      = [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]\n|leader      = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start  = 19 July 2011\n|term_end    = 20 March 2018\n|predecessor = [[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]\n|successor   = [[Jennie Formby]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1969|8|17}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse      = \n|children    = 2\n|alma_mater  = [[Abertay University]]\n}}\n'''Iain Mackenzie McNicol, Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''' (born 17 August 1969) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and [[trade union]]ist. From 2011 to 2018 he was [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]].<ref name=\"Stewart\">{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/23/labour-general-secretary-stands-down-from-position|title=Labour party general secretary stands down from position|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref> Previously he was National Political Officer of the [[GMB Union]].<ref name=bbc-20110719>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14204368 |title=Iain McNicol named as new Labour general secretary |publisher=BBC |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMcNicol began his involvement in political organising as president of the Student Union at [[Dundee Institute of Technology]] in 1991.<ref name=observer-20160709>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/09/labour-leaders-mp-collision-course-partys-soul-election-jeremy-corbyn |title=Labour leader and MPs set on collision course in a battle for party's soul |author=Daniel Boffey |newspaper=The Observer |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected National Campaigns and Membership Officer for [[Labour Students]],<ref name=progress-20110720>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2011/07/20/labours-new-general-secretary/ |title=Labour 's new general secretary |author=Luke Akehurst |publisher=Progress Online |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> and then acted as a Labour Party organiser and agent in south and east England from 1994 to 1997.<ref name=progress-20110720/><ref name=progress-20120525>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/05/25/changing-to-win/ |title=Changing to win |author=Iain McNicol |publisher=Progress Online |date=25 May 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=ph-20120927>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/social-affairs/politics/house/67381/street-fighting-man |title=Street Fighting Man |author=Paul Waugh, Sam Macrory |website=PoliticsHome |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[1997 United Kingdom general election]] at which Labour returned to office, McNicol served as a research, organisation, and political officer with the [[GMB Union]], and in 1998 was appointed a regional organiser for its Southern Region.<ref name=hp-20110726>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/07/26/labours-new-general-secre_n_908642.html |title=Labour's New General Secretary: His Dramatic Win And Why He Is The Insurgency Candidate |author=Dina Rickman |publisher=Huffington Post |date=26 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> In 2004, he was promoted to National Political Officer. He served in that capacity through to 2011, coordinating the political strategy of the union and representing its members\u2019 interests in both the public and private sector.<ref name=hp-20110726/><ref name=newstatesman-20110719>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/07/labour-party-mcnicol-general |title=Iain McNicol is the right man for the job |author=Will Straw |newspaper=New Statesman |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2011, Labour's [[National Executive Committee]] selected McNicol to become the party's next General Secretary under leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=bbc-20110719 />\n\nMcNicol's intention to stand down as General Secretary of the Labour Party was announced on 23 February 2018.<ref name=\"Stewart\"/> On 20 March 2018 he was succeeded by [[Jennie Formby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/93790/jennie-formby-appointed-labour-general-secretary|title=Jennie Formby appointed Labour general secretary in huge boost for Jeremy Corbyn|first=|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=20 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2018, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''', ''of West Kilbride in the County of Ayrshire''.<ref name=ph-20180518>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/house-lords-reform/news/95306/former-labour-general-secretary-iain-mcnicol |title=Former Labour general secretary Iain McNicol given peerage by Jeremy Corbyn |last=Schofield |first=Kevin |website=PoliticsHome |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62337|date=27 June 2018|page=11404}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 [[Jon Lansman]] the founder of [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] writing in the [[LabourList]] blog accused McNicol and his team of delaying action on handling [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism cases]] while he was General Secretary, and allowing a backlog of cases to build up that would damage the party and [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeremy Corbyn pushed for action on antisemitism \u2013 but was held back by bureaucracy |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/05/jeremy-corbyn-pushed-for-action-on-antisemitism-but-was-held-back-by-bureaucracy/ |publisher=Labourlist |accessdate=12 July 2019 |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Labour Party leadership election==\nIn June and July 2016, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that the office of the Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] believed that McNicol tried to prevent Corbyn from attending a key [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) meeting, and was alleged to be complicit in trying to exclude Corbyn from entering the second leadership election. It reported that senior figures in the trade union movement were discussing replacement options for McNicol in his General Secretary role.<ref name=ft-20160713>{{cite news |url=https://next.ft.com/content/b05f39a2-490b-11e6-b387-64ab0a67014c |title=Labour's McNicol targeted over role in coup |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/25/labour-leadership-contest-legal-documents-reveal-depth-of-split/ |title=Labour leadership contest: Legal documents reveal depth of split between Jeremy Corbyn and party 's general secretary |author=Ben Riley-Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA civil [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] legal challenge was brought by Labour donor and former parliamentary candidate [[Michael Foster (agent)|Michael Foster]], to contest the decision to allow Corbyn to be a candidate without having to secure any nominations from Labour MPs. The case went to court on 26 July 2016. McNicol was the first defendant on behalf of the members of the Labour Party. Corbyn applied to the court, and was accepted, to be a second defendant with his own legal team as Corbyn was \"particularly affected and particularly interested in the proper construction of the rules\" and that McNicol was \"being expected to vigorously defend a position which he regarded as incorrect prior to the NEC decision\".<ref name=telegraph-20160725/><ref name=guardian-20160720>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/jeremy-corbyn-wins-right-to-be-defendant-in-leadership-court-case |title=Jeremy Corbyn wins right to be defendant in leadership court case |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The High Court ruled that the NEC's decision that Corbyn should automatically be on the ballot was a correct interpretation of the [[Labour Party Rule Book]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/28/jeremy-corbyn-fights-off-court-challenge-labour-leadership-ballot|title=Jeremy Corbyn fights off court challenge over Labour leadership ballot|newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Walker|first1=Peter |last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev |last3=Mason|first3=Rowena |date=28 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=highcourt-20160728>>{{cite report |url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/judgment-foster-v-mcnicol-and-corbyn-20160728.pdf |title=Between: MICHAEL FOSTER and IAIN McNICOL (1) (sued on behalf of all other members of the Labour Party except the Claimant and the Second Defendant) and THE RT HON JEREMY CORBYN MP (2) |author=Mr Justice Foskett |publisher=Royal Courts of Justice id&#61;[2016] EWHC 1966 (QB) Case HQ16X02502 |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn additional [[Evangelou v McNicol|court case]] was brought against McNicol in August 2016 regarding the NEC's decision to disallow party members who had joined after 12 January 2016 from voting in the leadership election. The claimants won their case in the High Court, but this decision was overturned on [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|appeal]].<ref>BBC - [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/37077672 \"Labour leadership: Members drop voting legal challenge\"] 14 August 2016</ref> In late September, it was reported that a Labour party member was lodging a claim at the County Court in response to her suspension by the NEC and that it would cite McNicol as claimant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanary.co/2016/09/21/latest-twist-labour-purge-truly-astonishing-images/|title=The latest twist in the Labour 'purge' is truly astonishing [IMAGES]|date=2016-09-21|website=The Canary|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcNicol is married and has a son and daughter.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} He holds a black belt in [[karate]].<ref name=ph-20120927/> He attended Ardrossan Academy.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://labourlist.org/2012/07/iain-mcnicol-q-a/ Iain McNicol \u2013 Q & A], [[LabourList]], 19 July 2012\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jennie Formby]]}} \n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown|The Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Alan Haselhurst|The Lord Haselhurst]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Organised labour}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNicol, Iain}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Abertay Dundee]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Jeremy Corbyn]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=June 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2017}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name        = The Lord McNicol of West Kilbride\n|image       = Official portrait of Lord McNicol of West Kilbride crop 2.jpg\n|caption     = McNicol in 2019\n|office      = [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]\n|leader      = [[Ed Miliband]]<br />[[Harriet Harman]] {{small|(Acting)}}<br />[[Jeremy Corbyn]]\n|term_start  = 19 July 2011\n|term_end    = 20 March 2018\n|predecessor = [[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]\n|successor   = [[Jennie Formby]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth date and age|df=y|1969|8|17}}\n|birth_place = \n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]]\n|spouse      = \n|children    = 2\n|alma_mater  = [[Abertay University]]\n}}\n'''Iain Mackenzie McNicol, Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''' (born 17 August 1969) is a British [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] politician and [[trade union]]ist. From 2011 to 2018 he was [[General Secretary of the Labour Party]].<ref name=\"Stewart\">{{cite news|last=Stewart|first=Heather|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2018/feb/23/labour-general-secretary-stands-down-from-position|title=Labour party general secretary stands down from position|work=The Guardian|date=23 February 2018|accessdate=23 February 2018}}</ref> He sold Jeremy Corbyn down the river. Previously he was National Political Officer of the [[GMB Union]].<ref name=bbc-20110719>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-14204368 |title=Iain McNicol named as new Labour general secretary |publisher=BBC |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=19 July 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nMcNicol began his involvement in political organising as president of the Student Union at [[Dundee Institute of Technology]] in 1991.<ref name=observer-20160709>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/09/labour-leaders-mp-collision-course-partys-soul-election-jeremy-corbyn |title=Labour leader and MPs set on collision course in a battle for party's soul |author=Daniel Boffey |newspaper=The Observer |date=9 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nHe was elected National Campaigns and Membership Officer for [[Labour Students]],<ref name=progress-20110720>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2011/07/20/labours-new-general-secretary/ |title=Labour 's new general secretary |author=Luke Akehurst |publisher=Progress Online |date=20 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> and then acted as a Labour Party organiser and agent in south and east England from 1994 to 1997.<ref name=progress-20110720/><ref name=progress-20120525>{{cite news |url=http://www.progressonline.org.uk/2012/05/25/changing-to-win/ |title=Changing to win |author=Iain McNicol |publisher=Progress Online |date=25 May 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=ph-20120927>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/social-affairs/politics/house/67381/street-fighting-man |title=Street Fighting Man |author=Paul Waugh, Sam Macrory |website=PoliticsHome |date=27 September 2012 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[1997 United Kingdom general election]] at which Labour returned to office, McNicol served as a research, organisation, and political officer with the [[GMB Union]], and in 1998 was appointed a regional organiser for its Southern Region.<ref name=hp-20110726>{{cite news |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/2011/07/26/labours-new-general-secre_n_908642.html |title=Labour's New General Secretary: His Dramatic Win And Why He Is The Insurgency Candidate |author=Dina Rickman |publisher=Huffington Post |date=26 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> In 2004, he was promoted to National Political Officer. He served in that capacity through to 2011, coordinating the political strategy of the union and representing its members\u2019 interests in both the public and private sector.<ref name=hp-20110726/><ref name=newstatesman-20110719>{{cite news |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/blogs/the-staggers/2011/07/labour-party-mcnicol-general |title=Iain McNicol is the right man for the job |author=Will Straw |newspaper=New Statesman |date=19 July 2011 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 July 2011, Labour's [[National Executive Committee]] selected McNicol to become the party's next General Secretary under leader [[Ed Miliband]].<ref name=bbc-20110719 />\n\nMcNicol's intention to stand down as General Secretary of the Labour Party was announced on 23 February 2018.<ref name=\"Stewart\"/> On 20 March 2018 he was succeeded by [[Jennie Formby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/political-parties/labour-party/news/93790/jennie-formby-appointed-labour-general-secretary|title=Jennie Formby appointed Labour general secretary in huge boost for Jeremy Corbyn|first=|last=PoliticsHome.com|date=20 March 2018|publisher=|accessdate=19 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 June 2018, he was created a [[life peer]] as '''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride''', ''of West Kilbride in the County of Ayrshire''.<ref name=ph-20180518>{{cite news |url=https://www.politicshome.com/news/uk/constitution/house-lords-reform/news/95306/former-labour-general-secretary-iain-mcnicol |title=Former Labour general secretary Iain McNicol given peerage by Jeremy Corbyn |last=Schofield |first=Kevin |website=PoliticsHome |date=18 May 2018 |accessdate=1 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62337|date=27 June 2018|page=11404}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2019 [[Jon Lansman]] the founder of [[Momentum (organisation)|Momentum]] writing in the [[LabourList]] blog accused McNicol and his team of delaying action on handling [[Antisemitism in the UK Labour Party|antisemitism cases]] while he was General Secretary, and allowing a backlog of cases to build up that would damage the party and [[Jeremy Corbyn]]'s leadership.<ref>{{cite web |title=Jeremy Corbyn pushed for action on antisemitism \u2013 but was held back by bureaucracy |url=https://labourlist.org/2019/05/jeremy-corbyn-pushed-for-action-on-antisemitism-but-was-held-back-by-bureaucracy/ |publisher=Labourlist |accessdate=12 July 2019 |date=14 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n==2016 Labour Party leadership election==\nIn June and July 2016, the ''[[Financial Times]]'' reported that the office of the Labour leader [[Jeremy Corbyn]] believed that McNicol tried to prevent Corbyn from attending a key [[National Executive Committee]] (NEC) meeting, and was alleged to be complicit in trying to exclude Corbyn from entering the second leadership election. It reported that senior figures in the trade union movement were discussing replacement options for McNicol in his General Secretary role.<ref name=ft-20160713>{{cite news |url=https://next.ft.com/content/b05f39a2-490b-11e6-b387-64ab0a67014c |title=Labour's McNicol targeted over role in coup |author=Jim Pickard |newspaper=Financial Times |date=13 July 2016 |accessdate=14 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-20160725>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/07/25/labour-leadership-contest-legal-documents-reveal-depth-of-split/ |title=Labour leadership contest: Legal documents reveal depth of split between Jeremy Corbyn and party 's general secretary |author=Ben Riley-Smith |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nA civil [[High Court of Justice|High Court]] legal challenge was brought by Labour donor and former parliamentary candidate [[Michael Foster (agent)|Michael Foster]], to contest the decision to allow Corbyn to be a candidate without having to secure any nominations from Labour MPs. The case went to court on 26 July 2016. McNicol was the first defendant on behalf of the members of the Labour Party. Corbyn applied to the court, and was accepted, to be a second defendant with his own legal team as Corbyn was \"particularly affected and particularly interested in the proper construction of the rules\" and that McNicol was \"being expected to vigorously defend a position which he regarded as incorrect prior to the NEC decision\".<ref name=telegraph-20160725/><ref name=guardian-20160720>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/20/jeremy-corbyn-wins-right-to-be-defendant-in-leadership-court-case |title=Jeremy Corbyn wins right to be defendant in leadership court case |author=Jessica Elgot |newspaper=The Guardian |date=20 July 2016 |accessdate=20 July 2016}}</ref> The High Court ruled that the NEC's decision that Corbyn should automatically be on the ballot was a correct interpretation of the [[Labour Party Rule Book]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2016/jul/28/jeremy-corbyn-fights-off-court-challenge-labour-leadership-ballot|title=Jeremy Corbyn fights off court challenge over Labour leadership ballot|newspaper=The Guardian |last1=Walker|first1=Peter |last2=Syal|first2=Rajeev |last3=Mason|first3=Rowena |date=28 July 2016|accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref><ref name=highcourt-20160728>>{{cite report |url=https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/judgment-foster-v-mcnicol-and-corbyn-20160728.pdf |title=Between: MICHAEL FOSTER and IAIN McNICOL (1) (sued on behalf of all other members of the Labour Party except the Claimant and the Second Defendant) and THE RT HON JEREMY CORBYN MP (2) |author=Mr Justice Foskett |publisher=Royal Courts of Justice id&#61;[2016] EWHC 1966 (QB) Case HQ16X02502 |date=28 July 2016 |accessdate=29 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nAn additional [[Evangelou v McNicol|court case]] was brought against McNicol in August 2016 regarding the NEC's decision to disallow party members who had joined after 12 January 2016 from voting in the leadership election. The claimants won their case in the High Court, but this decision was overturned on [[Court of Appeal of England and Wales|appeal]].<ref>BBC - [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/amp/37077672 \"Labour leadership: Members drop voting legal challenge\"] 14 August 2016</ref> In late September, it was reported that a Labour party member was lodging a claim at the County Court in response to her suspension by the NEC and that it would cite McNicol as claimant.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.thecanary.co/2016/09/21/latest-twist-labour-purge-truly-astonishing-images/|title=The latest twist in the Labour 'purge' is truly astonishing [IMAGES]|date=2016-09-21|website=The Canary|access-date=2016-09-23}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMcNicol is married and has a son and daughter.{{citation needed|date=July 2016}} He holds a black belt in [[karate]].<ref name=ph-20120927/> He attended Ardrossan Academy.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://labourlist.org/2012/07/iain-mcnicol-q-a/ Iain McNicol \u2013 Q & A], [[LabourList]], 19 July 2012\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Ray Collins, Baron Collins of Highbury|Ray Collins]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[General Secretary of the Labour Party]]|years=2011\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jennie Formby]]}} \n{{s-prec|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Baron McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown|The Lord McCrea of Magherafelt and Cookstown]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Orders of precedence in the United Kingdom|Gentlemen]]'''<br />''Baron McNicol of West Kilbride'' '''}}\n{{s-fol|after=[[Alan Haselhurst|The Lord Haselhurst]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Labour Party}}\n\n{{Portal bar|Politics|United Kingdom|Organised labour}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McNicol, Iain}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Abertay Dundee]]\n[[Category:British trade unionists]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:Peers nominated by Jeremy Corbyn]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) officials]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Theojessop", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed trolling/vandal change.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Iain_McNicol"}
{"title_page": "Vikas Swarup", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-suffix = [[Indian Foreign Service|IFS]]\n| name        = Vikas Swarup\n| image       = VikasSwarup (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize   = 180px\n| caption     = Swarup in 2007\n| pseudonym   = \n|birth_date = 1963\n| birth_place = [[Allahabad]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| occupation  = [[Diplomat]] [[Indian Foreign Service|IFS]], Author\n| nationality = {{flag|India|name=Indian}}\n| spouse   = Aparna Swarup\n| office = [[Indian Foreign Secretary|Secretary of Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs]]<ref name=HB1>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/vikas-swarup-appointed-secretary-of-overseas-indian-affairs/article28399233.ece | title=Vikas Swarup appointed Secretary of Overseas Indian Affairs | date=12 July 2019 | newspaper=The Hindu Business Line | agency=PTI | accessdate=16 August 2019 }}</ref>\n| status = Incumbent\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| term_start = 1 August 2019\n| predecessor = ''Position Established''\n| office1   = [[High commissioner (Commonwealth)|Indian High Commissioner to Canada]]\n| term_start1 = 3 March 2017\n| term_end1  = 1 August 2019\n| predecessor1 = Vishnu Prakash<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/politics/vikas-swarup-external-affairs-ministry-spokesperson-india-ambassador-high-commissioner-to-canada|title=MEA Spokesperson Vikas Swarup Named High Commissioner to Canada|publisher=|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n| successor1 = ''To Be Appointed''\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister1 = [[Sushma Swaraj]]<br>[[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| office2      = [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Spokesperson of the Indian Ministry of External Affairs]]<br>[[Joint secretary to the Government of India|Joint Secretary (External Relations)]]\n| term_start2  = 18 April 2015\n| term_end2    = 28 February 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Syed Akbaruddin]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister2 = [[Sushma Swaraj]]\n| successor2   = Gopal Baglay\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Allahabad]]\n| signature   = \n| known_for   =  ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'' (2005)<br>''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'' (2008)<br>''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]'' (2013)\n| website     = {{url|http://vikasswarup.net}}\n}}\n\n'''Vikas Swarup''' (born 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/interviews/0023961-interview-vikas-swarup-the-author-of-qa-the-novel-behind-the-oscar-winning-film-slumdog-millionaire.html|title=Interview: Vikas Swarup - The author of Q&A, the novel behind the Oscar-winning film Slumdog Millionaire|date=24 January 2013|publisher=The Cambridge Student}}</ref> is an Indian diplomat and a well known writer. He is the current Secretary (PCV) at the [[Ministry of External Affairs, India]] and has previously as High Commissioner of India in Canada and has been the official spokesperson of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vikas Swarup to be new spokesperson of External Affairs Ministry|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/vikas-swarup-to-be-new-spokesperson-of-external-affairs-ministry/article7035772.ece|accessdate=14 March 2016|work=The Hindu|date=26 March 2015}}</ref> He presently serves as a Secretary to the Government of India for Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs. He is best known as the author of the novel ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'', adapted in film as ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', the winner of Best Film for the year 2009 at the [[Academy Awards]], [[Golden Globe Awards]] and [[BAFTA Awards]].\n\nSwarup joined the [[Indian Foreign Service]] in 1986 and served in [[Turkey]], the [[United States]], [[Ethiopia]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[South Africa]] and [[Japan]] in various Indian diplomatic missions. His other novels are ''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'' and ''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]''. In April 2015, he was appointed as the official spokesperson of the Ministry of External Affairs of India to head its [[Public Diplomacy|Public Diplomacy divisions]] at [[New Delhi]], succeeding [[Syed Akbaruddin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/slumdog-millionnaire-author-vikas-swarup-succeed-syed-akbaruddin-mea-spokesman-2174715.html|title=Slumdog Millionaire author Vikas Swarup to take over Syed Akbaruddin as MEA spokesperson|work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2019, the Ministry of Pensions, Personnel and Public Grievances announced that Swarup would be promoted to the rank of [[Secretary to the Government of India]], holding the newly created portfolio of Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs. He took office on 1 August 2019.<ref name=HB1 /> His replacement as Indian High Commissioner to Canada has not yet been named. \n\n==Early life and education==\nVikas Swarup was born in the historic Indian city, [[Allahabad]] in a family of lawyers.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.vikasswarup.net/bio/|title=Bio|work=vikasswarup.net}}</ref> He did his schooling at [[Boys' High School & College, Allahabad]] and pursued further studies at [[Allahabad University]] in [[Psychology]], [[History]] and [[Philosophy]].\n\n==Diplomatic career==\nSwarup is a career diplomat and joined Indian Foreign Service in 1986. He has served in different capacities in New Delhi and in India's missions abroad including his last assignment as High Commissioner of India to Canada followed by the post of the official spokesperson of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]. He also served in [[Ankara]], Washington D.C., [[Addis Ababa]], London, [[Pretoria]] and as Consul General in Osaka-Kobe, Japan.\n\n==Writing career==\n\n===''Q & A''===\nHis [[debut novel]], ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'', tells the story of how a penniless waiter in [[Mumbai]] becomes the biggest quiz show winner in history. Critically acclaimed in India and abroad, this international best-seller has been translated into 43 different languages. It was shortlisted for the Best First Book by the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] and won South Africa's [[Exclusive Books Boeke Prize]] in 2006, as well as the Prix Grand Public at the 2007 Paris Book Fair. It was voted winner of the Best Travel Read (Fiction) at the Heathrow Travel Product Award 2009.\n\nA [[BBC]] radio play based on the book won the Gold Award for Best Drama at the 2008 [[Sony Radio Academy Awards]] and the 2008 IVCA Clarion Award. [[Harper Collins]] brought out the audio book, read by [[Kerry Shale]], which won the Audie for best fiction audio book of the year. [[Film4]] of the UK had optioned the movie rights and the movie titled ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', directed by [[Danny Boyle]], was first released in the US to great critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|date=2010|title=Showcasing India Unshining: Film Tourism in Danny Boyle'sSlumdog Millionaire|journal=Third Text|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=471\u2013479|doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.491379|issn=0952-8822}}</ref> It won the People's Choice Award at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] and three awards (Best Film, Best Director and Most Promising Newcomer) at the [[British Independent Film Awards]] 2008. The [[National Board of Review]] picked ''Slumdog Millionaire'' as the best film of 2008. The movie swept five awards out of its six nominations at the [[Critics' Choice Awards]], and all four nominations awarded at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] including best director, picture, screenplay and score, and seven [[BAFTA Awards]]. It received ten [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nominations of which it won eight, including Best Picture and Best Director. From ''[[The NY Times]]'' report: \"[T]hough it had no actors nominated for prizes, [it also] swept many awards other than those on the top line, including prizes for cinematography, sound mixing, score and film editing. ''Slumdog'''s eight Oscars was the largest total won by a single film since ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'' won 11 in 2004.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/movies/awardsseason/23oscar.html \"A \u2018Slumdog\u2019 Kind of Night at the Oscar Ceremony\"] by [[Michael Cieply]] and [[David Carr (journalist)|David Carr]], ''The New York Times'', 23 February 2009. Retrieved 2\u201323\u201309.</ref> The film was released in the UK on 9 January 2009 and in India on 23 January with William Losch.\n\n===''Six Suspects''===\nSwarup's second novel ''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'', published by [[Transworld Publishers|Transworld]], was released on 28 July 2008 and has been translated into more than 30 languages. The US edition was published by [[Minotaur Books]] in 2009.  It was optioned for a film by the BBC and Starfield productions and [[John Hodge (screenwriter)|John Hodge]], who has been commissioned to write the screenplay.\n\n===''The Accidental Apprentice''===\nSwarup's third novel is ''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]'', published by Simon & Schuster (UK) in 2013.\n\n===Other works===\nSwarup's short story \"A Great Event\" was published in ''The Children's Hours: Stories of Childhood'', an anthology of stories about childhood to support [[Save the Children]] and raise awareness for its fight to end violence against children.\n\nSwarup has participated in the Oxford Literary Festival, the [[Turin International Book Fair]], the Auckland Writers' Conference, the [[Sydney Writers' Festival]], the [[Kitab Festival]] in New Delhi, the [[St. Malo]] International Book & Film Festival in France, the 'Words on Water' Literary Festival at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] in Johannesburg, the [[Jaipur Literature Festival]] in India, the Hay-on-Wye Festival in Wales and the Franschhoek Literary Festival in South Africa. In 2009 he participated in the 33rd [[Cairo International Film Festival]] as a jury member for the International Competition for Feature Digital Films.\n\nHe has written for ''TIME'', Newsweek, ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (UK), [[Outlook (Indian magazine)|''Outlook'']] magazine (India) and ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'' (France).\n\nVikas Swarup gives many motivational talks at institutions across the world.\n\n==Recognition==\nOn 21 September 2010 the [[University of South Africa]] (UNISA) conferred the degree of Doctor of Literature & Philosophy ([[honoris causa]]) on Swarup at a graduation ceremony in Pretoria.\n\nHe took over as the spokesperson of the Ministry of External Affairs on 18 April 2015.\n\n==Personal life==\nSwarup speaks Turkish apart from English and other Indian languages. He is married to Aparna, an artist, and the couple has two sons.<ref>http://www.vikasswarup.net/bio/</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]]\n*[[Taranjit Singh Sandhu]]\n*[[Vinay Mohan Kwarta]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3139511}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n2005-6078}}\n\n===Interviews and articles===\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/27/mumbai-terror-attacks-terrorism Vikas Swarup: Mumbai will recover from this, just as it has many times before]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/news/2005/feb/02inter1.htm The Rediff Interview/Vikas Swarup]\n* [http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/south-asia/slumdog-success-it-all-started-in-allahabad_100141686.html   How the story of Slumdog Millionaire started.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swarup, Vikas}}\n[[Category:Indian diplomats]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Allahabad alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian Foreign Service officers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian male writers]]\n[[Category:Indian male novelists]]\n[[Category:Indian male short story writers]]\n[[Category:High Commissioners of India to Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-suffix = [[Indian Foreign Service|IFS]]\n| name        = Vikas Swarup\n| image       = VikasSwarup (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize   = 180px\n| caption     = Swarup in 2007\n| pseudonym   = \n|birth_date = 1963\n| birth_place = [[Allahabad]], [[Uttar Pradesh]], [[India]]\n| occupation  = [[Diplomat]] [[Indian Foreign Service|IFS]], Author\n| nationality = {{flag|India|name=Indian}}\n| spouse   = Aparna Swarup\n| office = [[Indian Foreign Secretary|Secretary of Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs]]<ref name=HB1>{{cite news | url=https://www.thehindubusinessline.com/news/vikas-swarup-appointed-secretary-of-overseas-indian-affairs/article28399233.ece | title=Vikas Swarup appointed Secretary of Overseas Indian Affairs | date=12 July 2019 | newspaper=The Hindu Business Line | agency=PTI | accessdate=16 August 2019 }}</ref>\n| status = Incumbent\n| primeminister = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister = [[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| term_start = 1 August 2019\n| predecessor = ''Position Established''\n| office1   = [[High commissioner (Commonwealth)|Indian High Commissioner to Canada]]\n| term_start1 = 3 March 2017\n| term_end1  = 1 August 2019\n| predecessor1 = Vishnu Prakash<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thequint.com/news/politics/vikas-swarup-external-affairs-ministry-spokesperson-india-ambassador-high-commissioner-to-canada|title=MEA Spokesperson Vikas Swarup Named High Commissioner to Canada|publisher=|accessdate=3 August 2018}}</ref>\n| successor1 = ''To Be Appointed''\n| primeminister1 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister1 = [[Sushma Swaraj]]<br>[[Subrahmanyam Jaishankar]]\n| office2      = [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Spokesperson of the Indian Ministry of External Affairs]]<br>[[Joint secretary to the Government of India|Joint Secretary (External Relations)]]\n| term_start2  = 18 April 2015\n| term_end2    = 28 February 2017\n| predecessor2 = [[Syed Akbaruddin]]\n| primeminister2 = [[Narendra Modi]]\n| minister2 = [[Sushma Swaraj]]\n| successor2   = Gopal Baglay\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Allahabad]]\n| signature   = \n| known_for   =  ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'' (2005)<br>''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'' (2008)<br>''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]'' (2013)\n| website     = {{url|http://vikasswarup.net}}\n}}\n\n'''Vikas Swarup''' (born 1963)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tcs.cam.ac.uk/interviews/0023961-interview-vikas-swarup-the-author-of-qa-the-novel-behind-the-oscar-winning-film-slumdog-millionaire.html|title=Interview: Vikas Swarup - The author of Q&A, the novel behind the Oscar-winning film Slumdog Millionaire|date=24 January 2013|publisher=The Cambridge Student}}</ref> is an Indian diplomat and a well known writer. He is the current Secretary (PCV) at the [[Ministry of External Affairs, India]] and has previously as High Commissioner of India in Canada and has been the official spokesperson of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]] of India.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vikas Swarup to be new spokesperson of External Affairs Ministry|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/vikas-swarup-to-be-new-spokesperson-of-external-affairs-ministry/article7035772.ece|accessdate=14 March 2016|work=The Hindu|date=26 March 2015}}</ref> He presently serves as a Secretary to the Government of India for Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs. He is best known as the author of the novel ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'', adapted in film as ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', the winner of Best Film for the year 2009 at the [[Academy Awards]], [[Golden Globe Awards]] and [[BAFTA Awards]].\n\nSwarup joined the [[Indian Foreign Service]] in 1986 and served in [[Turkey]], the [[United States]], [[Ethiopia]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[South Africa]] and [[Japan]] in various Indian diplomatic missions. His other novels are ''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'' and ''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]''. In April 2015, he was appointed as the official spokesperson of the Ministry of External Affairs of India to head its [[Public Diplomacy|Public Diplomacy divisions]] at [[New Delhi]], succeeding [[Syed Akbaruddin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.firstpost.com/india/slumdog-millionnaire-author-vikas-swarup-succeed-syed-akbaruddin-mea-spokesman-2174715.html|title=Slumdog Millionaire author Vikas Swarup to take over Syed Akbaruddin as MEA spokesperson|work=Firstpost}}</ref>\n\nOn 12 July 2019, the Ministry of Pensions, Personnel and Public Grievances announced that Swarup would be promoted to the rank of [[Secretary to the Government of India]], holding the newly created portfolio of Consular, Passport, Visa and Overseas Indian Affairs. He took office on 1 August 2019.<ref name=HB1 /> His replacement as Indian High Commissioner to Canada has not yet been named. \n\n==Early life and education==\nVikas Swarup was born in the historic Indian city, [[Allahabad]] in a family of lawyers.<ref name=bio>{{cite web|url=http://www.vikasswarup.net/bio/|title=Bio|work=vikasswarup.net}}</ref> He did his schooling at [[Boys' High School & College, Allahabad]] and pursued further studies at [[Allahabad University]] in [[Psychology]], [[History]] and [[Philosophy]].\n\n==Diplomatic career==\nSwarup is a career diplomat and joined Indian Foreign Service in 1986. He has served in different capacities in New Delhi and in India's missions abroad including his last assignment as High Commissioner of India to Canada followed by the post of the official spokesperson of the [[Ministry of External Affairs (India)|Ministry of External Affairs]]. He also served in [[Ankara]], Washington D.C., [[Addis Ababa]], London, [[Pretoria]] and as Consul General in Osaka-Kobe, Japan.\n\n==Writing career==\n\n===''Q & A''===\nHis [[debut novel]], ''[[Q & A (novel)|Q & A]]'', tells the story of how a penniless waiter in [[Mumbai]] becomes the biggest quiz show winner in history. Critically acclaimed in India and abroad, this international best-seller has been translated into 43 different languages. It was shortlisted for the Best First Book by the [[Commonwealth Writers' Prize]] and won South Africa's [[Exclusive Books Boeke Prize]] in 2006, as well as the Prix Grand Public at the 2007 Paris Book Fair. It was voted winner of the Best Travel Read (Fiction) at the Heathrow Travel Product Award 2009.\n\nA [[BBC]] radio play based on the book won the Gold Award for Best Drama at the 2008 [[Sony Radio Academy Awards]] and the 2008 IVCA Clarion Award. [[Harper Collins]] brought out the audio book, read by [[Kerry Shale]], which won the Audie for best fiction audio book of the year. [[Film4]] of the UK had optioned the movie rights and the movie titled ''[[Slumdog Millionaire]]'', directed by [[Danny Boyle]], was first released in the US to great critical acclaim.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Mendes|first=Ana Cristina|date=2010|title=Showcasing India Unshining: Film Tourism in Danny Boyle'sSlumdog Millionaire|journal=Third Text|language=en|volume=24|issue=4|pages=471\u2013479|doi=10.1080/09528822.2010.491379|issn=0952-8822}}</ref> It won the People's Choice Award at the [[Toronto International Film Festival]] and three awards (Best Film, Best Director and Most Promising Newcomer) at the [[British Independent Film Awards]] 2008. The [[National Board of Review]] picked ''Slumdog Millionaire'' as the best film of 2008. The movie swept five awards out of its six nominations at the [[Critics' Choice Awards]], and all four nominations awarded at the [[Golden Globe Awards]] including best director, picture, screenplay and score, and seven [[BAFTA Awards]]. It received ten [[Academy Awards|Oscar]] nominations of which it won eight, including Best Picture and Best Director. From ''[[The NY Times]]'' report: \"[T]hough it had no actors nominated for prizes, [it also] swept many awards other than those on the top line, including prizes for cinematography, sound mixing, score and film editing. ''Slumdog'''s eight Oscars was the largest total won by a single film since ''[[The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King]]'' won 11 in 2004.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/movies/awardsseason/23oscar.html \"A \u2018Slumdog\u2019 Kind of Night at the Oscar Ceremony\"] by [[Michael Cieply]] and [[David Carr (journalist)|David Carr]], ''The New York Times'', 23 February 2009. Retrieved 2\u201323\u201309.</ref> The film was released in the UK on 9 January 2009 and in India on 23 January with William Losch.\n\n===''Six Suspects''===\nSwarup's second novel ''[[Six Suspects (novel)|Six Suspects]]'', published by [[Transworld Publishers|Transworld]], was released on 28 July 2008 and has been translated into more than 30 languages. The US edition was published by [[Minotaur Books]] in 2009.  It was optioned for a film by the BBC and Starfield productions and [[John Hodge (screenwriter)|John Hodge]], who has been commissioned to write the screenplay.\n\n===''The Accidental Apprentice''===\nSwarup's third novel is ''[[The Accidental Apprentice]]'', published by Simon & Schuster (UK) in 2013.\n\n===Other works===\nSwarup's short story \"A Great Event\" was published in ''The Children's Hours: Stories of Childhood'', an anthology of stories about childhood to support [[Save the Children]] and raise awareness for its fight to end violence against children.\n\nSwarup has participated in the Oxford Literary Festival, the [[Turin International Book Fair]], the Auckland Writers' Conference, the [[Sydney Writers' Festival]], the [[Kitab Festival]] in New Delhi, the [[St. Malo]] International Book & Film Festival in France, the 'Words on Water' Literary Festival at the [[University of the Witwatersrand]] in Johannesburg, the [[Jaipur Literature Festival]] in India, the Hay-on-Wye Festival in Wales and the Franschhoek Literary Festival in South Africa. In 2009 he participated in the 33rd [[Cairo International Film Festival]] as a jury member for the International Competition for Feature Digital Films.\n\nHe has written for ''TIME'', Newsweek, ''[[The Guardian]]'', ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' (UK), [[Outlook (Indian magazine)|''Outlook'']] magazine (India) and ''[[Lib\u00e9ration]]'' (France).\n\nVikas Swarup is also one of the finest public speakers, and has given many motivational talks at institutions across the world.\n\n==Recognition==\nOn 21 September 2010 the [[University of South Africa]] (UNISA) conferred the degree of Doctor of Literature & Philosophy ([[honoris causa]]) on Swarup at a graduation ceremony in Pretoria.\n\nHe took over as the spokesperson of the Ministry of External Affairs on 18 April 2015.\n\n==Personal life==\nSwarup speaks Turkish apart from English and other Indian languages. He is married to Aparna, an artist, and the couple has two sons.<ref>http://www.vikasswarup.net/bio/</ref>\n\n==See Also==\n*[[Harsh Vardhan Shringla]]\n*[[Taranjit Singh Sandhu]]\n*[[Vinay Mohan Kwarta]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|3139511}}\n*{{Worldcat id|lccn-n2005-6078}}\n\n===Interviews and articles===\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2008/nov/27/mumbai-terror-attacks-terrorism Vikas Swarup: Mumbai will recover from this, just as it has many times before]\n* [http://www.rediff.com/news/2005/feb/02inter1.htm The Rediff Interview/Vikas Swarup]\n* [http://www.thaindian.com/newsportal/south-asia/slumdog-success-it-all-started-in-allahabad_100141686.html   How the story of Slumdog Millionaire started.]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swarup, Vikas}}\n[[Category:Indian diplomats]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian novelists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:University of Allahabad alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian Foreign Service officers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian short story writers]]\n[[Category:Writers from Allahabad]]\n[[Category:Novelists from Uttar Pradesh]]\n[[Category